@node editorsdesk "From The Editor's Desk"
@toc contents
============================================================================
	            @{b}From The Editor's Desk@{ub} - by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
============================================================================

Hello again and welcome to another issue of WhatIFF?, the magazine that
is free but gives you so much! As I sit here writing at my A1200 I have
finally finished adding all the articles, reviews, guides and interviews.
It has been an exhausting summer here in Japan with the average temperature 
being 35 degrees, and as much as I enjoy working on my Amiga it has made it 
a bit of chore this issue, however enough of my moaning and onto this 
issue. 

We say hello to two new writers, Tristan Shiflett and Roald Strauss of who 
have contributed their expertise on anything Amiga audio related. Kevin 
Saunders is back with updates and John Scolieri has two guides regarding 
the fantastic PiStorm, Ivan Sorensen has a great piece on Amiga magazines
from the past today. Sadly Steve Lord was unable to make it for this issue 
however fingers are crossed he will be back for the December issue.

The magazine readership has been steadily growing and it has been a real
pleasure to have your comments. I have to give massive thanks out to
AmigaBill for doing a section of his programme on the magazine. It is a
real boost to all involved in the magazine when we see feedback like that.

Well  I will not keep you any longer, I hope you will enjoy this issue and
again if you you feel that you would like to contribute to the magazine
please contact us at: submissions@whatiff.info
 
@endnode

@node shelltalk "Free For All About Anything"
@toc contents
============================================================================
	               @{b}Shell Talk@{ub} - by: @{"Roald Strauss" link roaldstrauss} 
============================================================================

@{b}Physical media FTW!@{ub}

Hello. My name is MisthaLu and I'm addicted to physical media.

At our house we have no subscription to any streaming service whatsoever. 
We cancelled Netflix looong ago after years of disappointment over the 
poor selection of movies. All we have now are DVD's and Blu-ray's. And 
that's what we prefer. 

Here's why:

@{b}Availability@{ub}
First of all, a lot of the movies we like to watch - classic 80's movies 
for example - simply aren't available on any streaming service. So in these 
cases there really isn't any other option for us. Granted, some older 
movies that we like to watch, can be found freely and legal on YouTube 
and/or archives, but it's always in some crappy quality version, and never 
with the subtitles we want. And sure, there's the option of illegal 
downloads - and then spend hours trying to find a subtitle file that 
matches that particular version of the movie. No thanks. We feel more 
comfortable sticking with legal options.

@{b}We Want The Directors Cut@{ub}
Movies are a big interest of ours, and we usually prefer watching the 
Directors Cut version of the movie, rather than the standard theatrical 
version. Usually the streaming services only have the theatrical cut, and 
that's just not good enough for us.

@{b}Ours To Keep@{ub}
We get to keep movies - in their original version. Streaming services are 
way too "unstable". Movies are removed from the selection without warning. 
Some are even edited decades after release, because someone somewhere got 
offended by something silly. You need the original physical media to 
prevent this silliness.

@{b}Quality@{ub}
Streaming just can't match the quality of Blu-ray FullHD movies. Not to 
mention 4k movies. 'nuff said.

@{b}Price@{ub}
Contrary to popular belief, physical media is actually cheaper than 
streaming services.

If you want a "full" selection of new movies, no single streaming service 
is enough. Expect to pay at least 3 service fees (and still not be 
completely happy with the selection of available movies).

Meanwhile, the newly released blu-ray version of the movie you're waiting 
to see on your streaming service, is available in stores for roughly one 
third the expense, or less (depending on how many streaming services you're 
subscribed to of course).

Older movies can be found on physical media - often still wrapped in foil 
- here and there for almost nothing. Often less than 1 EUR.

@{b}Display@{ub}
Many people will emphasise the advantage of streaming: All your movies 
doesn't take up any space! But if you're someone who actually prefer your 
movies to take up space, and be displayed on the shelves in the living-room 
for a cosy atmosphere, then streaming is not an advantage at all, is it?

@{b}No Interruptions@{ub}
With the DVD or Blu-ray we're not risking any annoying interruptions due to 
problems with the Internet connection or the service provider. While I admit 
this is rare, we did experience it quite often at one point, and it was 
extremely annoying.

@{b}Bonus Content@{ub}
Always nice to watch. Especially gag reels.
Yes I know you can always find these on YouTube, but as with everything 
online: You never know how long it'll be available, and you also have to 
watch 2-3 commercials before getting to it. Not worth it.

People who advocate streaming often argue with stuff like "Oh, but what if 
you take a break watching a certain show, and get back to it a month later 
- you can't remember how far you got! Streaming services remembers that for 
you!" Yes they absolutely do - and blu-ray does too! Even years after the 
disc was last played, the player can remember how far you got.

It is true though, that some blu-ray discs doesn't offer this feature - 
because the manufacturer can choose not to add it, for whatever reason. But 
the technology does support it. Even for shows spanning multiple discs - 
the blu-ray player will tell you which disc to insert, and start playing 
the next episode.

Even in cases where the manufacturer chose not to include this feature, 
there are still players - even DVD players - that remembers how far you 
got. So shut up already.

@endnode

