@node omniportreview "Hardware review: Omniport"
@toc reviews
============================================================================
             @{b}Hardware Review: OmniPort for Amiga 1200@{ub} - by @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
============================================================================

@{b}Product Name@{ub}
OmniPort - Multi port adapter for Amiga 1200

@{b}Developed By@{ub}
Alinea Computer

@{b}Available From@{ub}
amiga-shop.net
       
@{b}Price@{ub}
25.95 EUR
  
@{b}Hardware/Software Requirements@{ub}
Amiga 1200 with free expansion port

@{b}Test Machine@{ub}
Amiga 1200/OS3.2/TF1260/Indivison AGA Mk3/A314-CP

@{b}Review@{ub}

Omni - of all things, is an adept for the adapter from Alinea Computer.

For most of the A1200's life the rear expansion port has been mostly
limited to SCSI ports or more recently video port adapters. However the
OmniPort is the first board to really make use of the free space at the 
back of the Amiga.

In the famous words of the Cat "What is it?" - for those who do not know
check out Red Dwarf series 2 episode 'Stasis Leak'. Well enough of my
Red Dwarf geekery onto the review ...

The OmniPort is a small board that can be screwed into your A1200 
motherboard, it provides two USB ports, one HDMI and one micro sd slot.
The HDMI connector is compatible with the Indivision AGA Mk3 and if you
have a Mk2 there is an additional cable available. The USB ports can be
used with RapidRoad USB or Subway USB card. The Micro SD port can be
connected to the internal SD card on a Vampire or interal IDE port with
an additional adapter. Those with A1200.net cases will be happy to hear 
that the board also fits without issue. The Indivision AGA Mk3 video port
unfortunately does not fit into the screw space on A1200.net cases so the 
OmniPort is ideal for those with a Mk3 and A1200.net case.

@{b}Installation@{ub}

To install the board you will need take off the top cover, keyboard and 
remove the floppy drive or Gotek. From here it is a simple case of aligning
the screw hole and tightening the screw. Another nice feature of the 
OmniPort is the included backplate which is available in a variety of 
colours to suit your case. I chose the transparent one as my case is an 
A1200.net transparent one. Fitting the cover can be a little tricky and
requires some considerable pushing. Once the board is securely tightened
and the rear plate in place, you can connect your cables. For my situation
I only have the Indivision AGA Mk3 to connect, which was the main reason 
for purchasing the OmniPort. Again the necessary cables were already
included and it was just a simple case of plug and arrange the cables.

Once the case was back on I could view my work, the transparent panel did
not match my case exactly it still looked a lot better than before. Having
the HDMI cable secured tightly is a bit relief and having the option of 
adding USB capability or changing my internal HD to an SD card is very 
useful.

The OmniPort fills a need that 10 years ago that would not have been
necessary but the numerous upgrades and addititions to the A1200 this 
little board has become quite the essential purchase.

@{b}Final Thoughts@{ub}

I have found that the Amiga has become a black hole of sorts, with each
passing year there are more and more ways to upgrade and keep your Amiga
current. And amid all this the poor A1200 becomes quite a mess of dangling
cables and wires. The OmniPort is something that addresses a need for 
cleaning up that mess. I find it to be very reasonably priced at 26 EUR and
adds a bit of future proofing. You do not have to add USB capablity to use
the card but if you do in the future then you do not need to suffer hanging
cables out of the case or worse cutting holes into it.

On a final note, I did not mention in the review the use of the OmniPort 
with the PiStorm. For those of you who have a PiStorm and use the internal
SD card, it can be a hassle changing the card. The OmniPort can be used with
the internal PiStorm SD card with a small adapter, negating the need to open
your case each time you want to change the SD card. If you have either an 
Indivision Mk3, A1200.net case, Subway, RapidRoad or/and PiStorm then this
board is a great addition to your Amiga. Thank to Alinea Computer for their
fast shipping and reasonable prices.
 
@endnode

@node amigakitledreview "Hardware review: Amiga Kit LED"
@toc reviews
============================================================================
    @{b}Hardware Review: A1200 Triple LED Adapter (AmigaKit)@{ub} - by @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
============================================================================

@{b}Product Name@{ub}
A1200 Triple LED Adapter

@{b}Developed By@{ub}
AmigaKit

@{b}Available From@{ub}
amigakit.com
       
@{b}Price@{ub}
9.29 GBP
  
@{b}Hardware/Software Requirements@{ub}
Amiga 1200

@{b}Test Machine@{ub}
Amiga 1200/OS3.2/TF1260/Indivison AGA Mk3/A314-CP

@{b}Review@{ub}

LED Adapters for the A1200 are two a penny, every Amiga shop is selling
their version of the board and with each company comes variations with the
board. For some reason I believed that we had reviewed an LED board in a
previous issue but after checking I do not see one. So this has altered my
review a bit.

To begin with, my LED light had stopped working due to being caught 
numerous times on the keyboard hole, the cable having been pulled out. At
this time I went in search for an LED replacement and found one by Sordan
for a great price, it also had the added advantage of having a plug at both
ends of the cable. However the cable itself was very thin and as I had 
suspected it eventually broke. So it was time to find another LED adapter
and one that was more sturdy this time.

Back in the day magazines would get sent stuff to review but with the market
being much smaller now we do not have the luxury of having things sent to us
for review. This means that we have to bargain hunt which in hindsight works
probably better for the reader.

So to make a long story short, I eventually found an LED adapter that looked
like what I was hoping for from AmigaKit. My main criterias were 1) a thick
cable, 2) plugs at both ends, 3) fits into an A1200.net case. The AmigaKit
adapter fit all three. The other added benefit of the AmigaKit adapter was
the option to change the colours of the LEDs. So for example if you miss 
the red LED for power from the earlier Amigas you can have that for your 
A1200. You are limited to red, yellow and green though. I chose green for
power, yellow for the floppy disk and red for the hard disk. It would have
been nice if they had more colours available however it is very useful being
able choose even out of the three.

@{b}From England to Japan@{ub}

Ordering from AmigaKit was a fast and easy process as usual, however I did 
run into their 'extended' processing time for orders which was quickly 
sorted after e-mailing and posting on EAB. AmigaKit is a great company that
has been around for a long time servicing us Amiga users when there was no
one else. Saying that, it is sad to see how their customer service has gone
down hill over the years.

Once the adapter was sent it quickly arrived, as usual their packing cannot
be beat. The adapter is very solidly built, there are two LEDs together but
it is difficult to see the line when in use. Installation was easy and there
were no issues with the lights fitting into my A1200.net case, there is 
about 2mm of space either side which was a bit of a dissapointment. The 
cable is thick and sturdy with the connector on the top of the board. This
made it a bit difficult to plug in the cable, especially if you have stubby
fingers like myself. Placing the plug on the side or below would have made
it a bit easier to access.

Once installed the LEDs were bright and nicely lit up my transparent case.
I was happy with the order of LEDs I had chosen but at the same time missed
the original green, yellow, orange configuration.

@{b}Final Thoughts@{ub}

Being able to unplug the LED adpater from the keyboard is a small but not
insignificant detail if you are often opening your case. The AmigaKit 
adapter is very good in this regard, the cable is strong, the lights are
bright and you can choose the order they are installed. Even the slightly
difficult access of the port on the board is not that much of a big deal.

If you are looking for a replacement LED adapter for your A1200 the AmigaKit
board is a good choice at a reasonable price, it is compatible with the 
newer cases and has a limited range of options and most importantly has a
thick cable and can be uplugged at both ends. 

@endnode

@node imagefxreview "Software Review: ImageFX 4.5"
@toc reviews
============================================================================
	   @{b}Software Review: ImageFX 4.5@{ub} - by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
============================================================================

@{b}Product Name@{ub}
ImageFX 4.5

@{b}Developed By@{ub}
Nova Design, Inc.

@{b}Available From@{ub}
AmiStore
apps.amistore.net/imagefx/
       
@{b}Price@{ub}
26.31 GBP
  
@{b}Hardware/Software Requirements@{ub}
KS 2.1+, 2MB Ram, 20MB+ HHD Space

@{b}Test Machine@{ub}
Amiga 1200 + PiStorm/TF1260

@{b}Review@{ub}

When you think of graphics in the 80s and 90s the Amiga arguably was the
leading platform with its 4096 colours available from the get go and
programmes such as DigiPaint allowing the user to edit photographs it was 
the machine to have. Almost forty years later and the rest of the world 
has caught up and surpassed the Amiga, making it irrelevant when it comes 
to digital graphics, or is it?
 
If we look at the later Amiga models, mainly the AGA machines the HAM-8 
mode is a great substitute for 24-BIT displays, tool that up with an 
accelerator and your old Amiga can become quite the image manipulator. 
What we need is modern software and while technically ImageFX 4.5 was 
released in 2020 it is still the newest commercial image processing
software the Amiga has. So, lets take a look and see how it has fared
after three years.

Originally I had planned to purchase the CD version in the hopes of
receiving a physical manual with it but it turned out that the CD
version was just that. As such I went for the digital download instead.
Purchasing was smooth through the AMIStore App Store. A-EON Technology Ltd.
had purchased the source code and future development rights from Woodall
Design LLC in 2015. The latest version runs on Amiga OS and Morph OS.
 
While the purchase went smoothly I did not receive my key due to the 
some issue with the screen update. However a quick e-mail got me sorted
with a download key.

@{b}Installation@{ub}

You have a number of options when starting the installer:

	* Install ImageFX 4.5
	* Install ImageFX 4.5 Extras
	* Install/Remove Hooks and Modules
	* Install AnimBrushes
	* Remove ImageFX 4.5
	* Remove ImageFX Extras Only
	* Install PowerStation

When you choose 'Install ImageFX4.5' another list of options will come up
and they are:

	* Install All Versions
	* Don't Install Optimized Versions
	* Install for 68020/68030 with Floating Point Unit
	* Install for 68040
	* Install for 68040 with Floating Point Unit
	* Install for 68060

Choosing the version suitable for your system is quite easy, the only issue
is if you have a machine with an LC060, in this case you will need to choose
'Don't Install Optimized Versions'. It takes a little while to install 
everything so during this time it might be a good idea to grab a drink or
sandwich.

Under ClassicWB I had no issues with installation and loading the programme
however when I tried to load up a picture be it a JPEG or IFF an error 
requestor popped up. After much head scratching it seemed that there is 
something causing an issue with my instaal of ClassicWB. To get ImageFX to 
work and load images I had to use Workbench 3.2 or BetterWB 3.2. Under 3.2 
images loaded without any issues. So please note that if you are running 
ClassicWB and want to use ImageFX 4.5 it might be worthwhile upgrading to 
OS3.2 first.

@{b}What's New?@{ub}

If you have used ImageFX before then the layout of 4.5 will be familiar, 
albeit now everything is contained with in floating windows. As far as I 
can see there is not too much difference regarding the filters and 
effects from previous versions. Clicking on `Filter` will present you 
with the following options: 

	- Dynamic Range
	- Histogram Equalisation
	- Colour Limit
	- Anti Alias
	- R.I.P
	- Video Filter
	- Median Filter
	- Remove Grain
	- Colour Balancing
	- Count Colours 

Comparing that to ImageFX 2, the filter options are exactly the same.

Distort provides more options however with the newer Image FX:

	ImageFX 2            ImageFX 4.5
	- Distort            - Displace
	- Wave Distort       - Wave Distort
	- Swirl              - Swirl
	- Warp               - Warp
	- Polar Blur         - Polar Blur
	- Mosaic             - Mosaic
	- Polar Mosaic       - Polar Mosaic
	- Spherize           - Spherize
	- Dream              - Dream
                    	     - Liquid
                     	     - Bubble 

Effect has also been boosted with three more options:

	ImageFX 2           ImageFX 4.5                   
	- Remove Feature    - Remove Feature
	- Oil Paint         - Oil Paint
	- Disperse          - Disperse
	- Roughen           - Roughen
	- Apply Texture     - Apply Texture
	- Straw             - Straw
	- Crystallize       - Crystallize
	- Radial Star       - Radial Star
	- Lens Flare        - Lens Flare
	- Paint FX          - Paint FX
	- Hockney Tiling    - Hockney Tiling
	- Lightning         - Lightning
                    	    - Film Grain
                    	    - Fire
                    	    - Sparkle

Aside for the additions to Distort and Effect, the major difference 
between Image FX 2 and 4.5 is the interface, layers and a more built in 
hooks. The updated interface is a welcome update and makes using it with 
a graphics board a much better experience. The ability to have numerous 
windows open makes for a faster workflow. Thankfully the visual overhaul 
has not made the programme harder to use, if you have used ImageFX before 
then you will be right at home with the familiar buttons and layout.
  
ImageFX is different from other programmes in how it handle file creation
an example of this would be when you want to create a new image/document.

With ImageFX you do not create a new file or document, instead you create 
a new `Buffer`, which can be done by clicking the `Buffer` button and then 
setting the dimensions, DPI, and RGB/Greyscale. Click on 'OK' and a window 
will pop up with desired settings. It is possible to load in a palette and 
apply it to your image or using the sliders set your own custom colours. 
I'll admit to it being a little confusing at first and requires more 
exploration. If you are used to the colour palettes in DPaint or 
Brillinace it could be a little intimidating at first. But we should bear 
in mind ImageFX is not an art package persay but an image processor. And 
this is where it really excels, the variety of filters, effects and 
additional hooks makes this the best image processor on the Amiga. While 
some of the actions can seem a bit clumsy by modern standards it still a 
powerful programme.

As a test in modern usage I loaded up some photos from a holiday. The 
photos were taken with a Nikon D3500, at the maximum resolution of the 
camera. Loading the image took a long time, around 2 minutes even with my 
TF1260 and PiStorm 32-lite connected. If possible using the onboard IDE on 
the TF1260 or the internal SD card of the PiStorm will make a difference 
in load times.

Once loaded I reduced the size to something more Amiga friendly. Dragging 
out the window will not enlarge the image, only the window. To do that you 
need to click on the (+/-) buttons. It took some experimentation and 
searching of buttons but I managed to distort some photos, cut them out 
and paste them into another image. Render times were fast, especially with 
the PiStorm, the TF1260 was slower but the screen update was faster. 
Hopefully a future update of will improve the chipram access and slower 
screen update.

@{b}Final Thoughts@{ub}

ImageFX 4.5 is a welcome upgrade, the new interface looks great, the use of 
layers and extra filters have all kept ImageFX at the forefront of Amiga
image processors. The ability to load and save a large variety of file
formats makes this the image processor to go to. With all that power comes
complexity and it will take time to learn how to use ImageFX to its full
potential.

At the beginning of the review I mentioned that there was no printed manual
with the CD, but there is an AmigaGuide manual included. It is a very well
written and layed out guide and I suggest you keep it on hand when first
using ImageFX. While it would have been nice to have some examples of how
to do certain tasks it is still very helpful. During my research I did
find a manual for sale on the Barnes and Noble website for 17.99 USD, but 
it is only an eBook title. 

If you are looking to do some serious image editing with your Amiga then
ImageFX 4.5 should be your first stop. It can be used with the standard
Amiga native modes or RTG and is very smooth on accelerated Amigas. 
                                              
@endnode

@node cd32bookreview "Book review: CD32 Disc Reference Guide"
@toc reviews
============================================================================
          @{b}Book Review: CD32 Disc Reference Guide@{ub} - by @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
============================================================================

@{b}Product Name@{ub}
CD32 Disc Reference Guide

@{b}Written By@{ub}
Amiga Jay

@{b}Available From@{ub}
amigajay.itch.io
ebay.co.uk
       
@{b}Price@{ub}
Physical 22.95 GBP
Digital 10 GBP
  
@{b}Review@{ub}

I came across the CD32 book during my times trawling through Twitter or as
it is now known as X(?!). Twitter is a great place to find out about new
Amiga projects and the CD32 Disc Reference Guide is one of them. Written
by AmigaJay it covers all 252 CD32 retail releases each with screenshots 
and a short review. The book is comes in at 260 pages all in full colour
and is a very portable A5 size.

There are two versions available, the PDF and physical book, the physical
book can be bought from eBay however due to the high shipping rate put on
by eBay I contacted AmigaJay direct to buy straight from him. He sent the 
book promptly with tracking.

First Impressions

The book arrived after about a week and from the outset looks very 
professional with a cover of Zool standing on a flying CD and part of a
CD32 in the bottom right corner. The cover is thick and glossy with the
internal pages matte but also nice and thick. You get a breakdown of the
contents on page 4.

	Games - 161 titles
	Entertainment - 19 titles
	Education - 4 titles
	Productivity - 21 titles
	Reference - 23 titles
	After-Market Games - 24 titles
	Cancelled Titles - 185 titles
	CD32 Disc Stats

As you can see the book does not only cover games but the whole spectrum
of software that is available for the venurable CD32. On each page you get
images of the game disk cover, rear, CD image, title screen and screenshot.
At the bottom right is a rating from A-F and a short paragraph of text
explaining a bit about the game and rating.

While I do not own a CD32 anymore, back when it first came out I was quick
to buy the Dangerous Streets pack, the book is a very entertaining read. 
Sometimes it is nice to have something that you can just dig into quickly 
have a look around and maybe learn of a new title that you can play on a
real CD32 or via emulation. I was surprised at the amount of titles that
were released in the CD32s short lifespan and more so the newer titles 
that have come out. It seems the same old story though with the newer
titles again not taking advantage of the CD32 hardware.

@{b}Final Thoughts@{ub}

If you have any interest in the CD32 then this is a great addition to your
bookshelf. You do not have to own an CD32 to enjoy the content and it is 
presented in a very pleasant manner. AmigaJay has released another book
the CDTV Disc Reference Guide which is a bit cheaper than the CD32 book
coming in at 3 GBP if you want to read more about the Amiga CD machines.
Releasing the book in A5 format was very smart, I think if it had been
in A4 the book would not have been as useful. As it stands the small size
makes it a very nice way to read about the games and other software 
releases for the last officially released Commodore Amiga computer.  

@endnode

