@node cyberpunks2review "Game Review: CyberPunks 2 Next Generation"
@toc gamereviews
============================================================================
        @{b}Game Review: @CyberPunks 2@{ub} - by @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
============================================================================

@{b}Product Name@{ub}
CyberPunks - Next Generation

@{b}Developed By@{ub}
Programming, Graphics, Audio by Adrian Robert Cummings

@{b}Available From@{ub}
softwareamusements.com/mutationsoftware/index.html
       
@{b}Price@{ub}
Digital 10.99 GBP
Boxed 16.99 GBP
  
@{b}Hardware/Software Requirements@{ub}
AGA Amiga
  
@{b}Test Machine@{ub}
Amiga 1200/TF1260/OS 3.2.2/Indivision AGA Mk3
  
@{b}Review@{ub}

The original CyberPunks was released in 1993, available for ECS Amigas it
featured bold and colourful graphics, with cartoony characters. With the 
sequence released 30 years later we have updated and more "mature" looking
graphics. Having played the original in 1993 I had found it a fun but quite
a hard game, including the time limit.

So what has changed aside from there being a 30 year hiatus?

The main differences are that the game is now supports only AGA machines, 
you can have two players at once and there is no time limit. The game can
be purchased as a boxed game or digital download. I decided to go for the
digital download as I do not have the space for keeping boxed games though
the boxed version is tempting being only 6 pounds more. The gameplay has
stayed the same with a top down view, the player needs to shoot the baddies
and find keys to open doors, force field bypass circuits to deactivate the
security force fields and MediPacks if you are losing energy. This time
around if you pick up a MediPack it will affect your whole team. Collect
Gold and Siler Crypto to earn enough money to buy upgrades, use the map
to find your location and even gamble your crypto to give you the chance
to buy more expensive items.

There is a variety of weapons that can be found throughout the game, they
are:
	* Basic Assault Weapon
	* Orb Launcher
	* Twin Laser
	* Flame Thrower
	* Special Weapons, these can only be bought from the terminal
	* SmartBombUnit (use the spacebar to activate) Great for bosses!

@{b}How Does It Play?@{ub}

I found CyberPunks 2 to be a very enjoyable game, more so than the orginal
one from 1993. The gameplay has been made simpler, the graphics are good,
more about them later, the music and sound effects are very effective and
the gameplay is very nicely set. Quickly I found myself getting into the 
game and time quickly flew by. Before I knew it already an hour had passed
by, which is a great mark of a game. The control was tight and I had no
issues controlling the characters with my wireless Commotron pad. An 
interesting mechanic of the game is that if you want everyone to fire in
the same direction you need to tap in the same direction three times. It
took me a while to realise this but once I had it figured out it became
second nature. The first stage is not very hard at all but it is big, your
mission objective is to save AmigaBill from his alien captors and the level
ends in a hilarious scene with AmigaBill.

Each time you finish a level you are provided with a level code which can 
be entered from the title screen options menu. I was very happy to have this
since the levels are quite large.

The graphics have changed quite a bit from the original game and I am not 
sure if it is for the better. They look less cartoony and more 'kick ass' 
but considering this is an AGA only game it seems to lack colour and is 
very dithered. In this regard the original ECS game colourwise looks better
but the actual sprite design is better in CyberPunks 2. Things get better
in later levels but it still looks like an ECS game.

The music and sound effects are great, very catchy music suiting each of 
the stages. Sound effects are spot on and remind me of shooters from the
Megadrive and SNES, they have the same kind of muffled but bassy explosions
and shooting sounds. When shooting with the laser it is just pure auditory
bliss, reminding me of scenes from Aliens.

Will It Install?

CyberPunks 2 comes on two disks and is only available as an ADF, if you 
wish to run it from your hard disk you need to abide by the limited 
directory settings of:

	dh0:CyberPunks2
	dh0:Games/CyberPunks2
	dh1:CyberPunks2
	dh1:Games/CyberPunks2 

I found installing the game with the WHDLoad installer made more sense than
the suggested installation. Originally I had some trouble running the game
on my machine which is an A1200 with a TF1260. I found out that by disabling
the CPUSPEED SPEED=65 from my user startup allowed the game to run. Since
then I have had no issues. 

@{b}Final Thoughts@{ub}

I had enjoyed the original and was looking forward to the sequel, the 
updated graphics while looking more like an ECS game work well. Moving
away from the cartoony style was a smart move. The gameplay has been
cleaned up and has made it more accessible and enjoyable. Overall I have
really enjoyed this game and having AmigaBill in it is just the topping
on a great game. Don't let the graphics put you off from videos online
or screenshots, this is a very well constructed game that oozes gameplay
and lots of fun. 
  
@{b}Pros and Cons@{ub}
+ Improved gameplay and mechanics
+ Very enjoyable shooter
+ Music and sound effects are spot on 
+ Large enough to keep you occupied for a while
- Graphics are good but there is too much dithering going on that makes
  it look like an OCS/ECS game

@{b}Scores@{ub}
Gameplay: 8.5/10
Graphics: 7/10
Sound:    9/10
Overall:  8.2/10 - Incredibly enjoyable arcade shooting fun than sounds and
                   looks great! Buy now!

@endnode


@node nightshiftreview
@toc gamereviews
============================================================================
                @{b}Game Review: NightShift@{ub} - by @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
============================================================================

@{b}Product Name@{ub}
NightShift

@{b}Developed By@{ub}
Eclectic Imaginations

@{b}Available From@{ub}
nightshift.cx
       
@{b}Price@{ub}
Free
  
@{b}Hardware/Software Requirements@{ub}
AGA Amiga, 2mb Chip Ram, OS3.x, 23mb hard disk space, PAL output
  
@{b}Test Machine@{ub}
Amiga 1200/TF1260/OS 3.2.2/Indivision AGA Mk3
  
@{b}Review@{ub}

Last issue we had a look at NeonNoir a cyberpunk point and click adventure
game and this time around again we have another cyberpunk adventure set in 
2039 Boston. Exclusive to the Amiga it is available for free from Aminet or
the official website: www.nightshift.cx.

It will take a little while to download on a real Amiga as the game comes 
in at 23mb, however once you have it downloaded it is a simple case of
extracting the file and copying it to your desired location, no need for
an installer or WHDLoad. What makes the game stand out from the get go are
the HAM8 graphics and music. The developer has taken an interesting route
by not using mod music but streaming music from the hard disk. This makes
for a great soundtrack but also means a lot of hard disk access, so expect
to see your HD light blinking most of the time. It should be mentioned that
the game multitasks which is a welcome feature, as I write this review in
ProText I have the game running in the background, very nice!

After you have loaded up the game, you get a nice title screen with some
synthpop music streaming from the hard disk, you are unable to do anything
until the music has stopped streaming. Once it has finished you can choose
from the menu on the left, Start, Resume, Exit. Selecting Start will take
you to the first screen which introduces your main protagnist, Sean, along 
with a profile picture. The following three screens set the scene to which
you will be playing in. In  nutshell the United States has been divided 
into two nations, the FSA Federal States of America and the RNA Republic of
America. The game deals with the themes of surveillance and control by 
large corporations and governments. Finally another loading screen pops up 
with the text 'Chapter One: Night out', it is here you are introduced to 
the game proper with five action icons above, a picture of your bedroom on 
the right and text on the left side. The icons from the left provide the 
following actions: Game Options, Check Date/Time, Check News, View Map, and 
Use Phone.

From here is a simple case of moving the mouse around and click on hotspots,
when you hover above a hotspot text will appear on the left. Unfortunately
the mouse cursor does not change, it stays the same standard Amiga cursor
which makes it a little difficult to play. Used to the standard system
used in point and click games I was automatically expecting the pointer to
change. From here on you need to explore the game, clicking around the
areas, travelling via the subway to other parts of the city and meet people.
At the beginning of the game most locations are not available, you will have
to meet certain people and travel to other places before you can even go 
into the mall for example.

Once you get the hang of the game mechanics and how to progress it becomes
more enjoyable and the story is quite interesting keeping you in the edge
of your seat at times. Crypto currency features a lot in the game so if 
you have a even a passing interest in it you will find this a very 
enjoyable. The game can only be progressed by figuring out the puzzles and
riddles which means that it might be bit hard for non-native English
speakers to enjoy the game.
  
@{b}Final Thoughts@{ub}

I will not ruin the game by going over the story but there are few things
that I would like to address. The game looks very nice, the HAM8 graphics
are beautiful and really pop out of the screen. Saying that the music is a
bit of an issue, while it sounds great you are the mercy of it. For example
when you get to a new location the game will load background effects, this
effectively stops the game as the hard disk is maxed out streaming the
sound effects, you are unable to do anything during this time. This makes
for a frustrating and jolting gameplay experience.

However I would not let this dissaude you from trying out the game, a bit 
of perserverance and patience will reward you with a very enjoyable game 
play experience and a story with a lot depth. 
  
@{b}Pros and Cons@{ub}
+ Beautiful graphics
+ Great music and sound effects
+ Story interesting once it gets going
- Music streaming can be jarring to gameplay

@{b}Scores@{ub}
Gameplay: 7/10
Graphics: 9/10
Sound:    7/10
Overall:  7.6/10 - A beautiful looking game that is hamstrung by loading and
                   audio issues.

@endnode

