@node rtgpistorm "PiStorm 32-lite RTG Setup"
@toc guides
=============================================================================
          @{b}How to install RTG on a PiStorm32-lite@{ub} - by: @{"John Scolieri" link johnscolieri}
=============================================================================

Following up on my Issue 10 review of my PiStorm32-lite accelerator in my 
Amiga 1200 I've decided to check out how RTG works on it. As there is 
currently no other PiStorm32 model (at least from the time of me typing 
this) and the 'lite' label was added to mitigate component shortage
problems at the time of it's release so to save a few keystrokes I'll be 
calling it Storm32 from now on :-)

Before we start you need to have either a second monitor handy or a monitor 
that supports VGA and HDMI or DVI or Display Port. Also it's important to 
note that RTG with Emu68 does not provide a flicker fixer or scan doubler 
so your system needs to already have one installed or you need to have a 
monitor that can sync to Amiga frequencies/ screen modes. I personally use 
one monitor with a HDMI splitter box as seen in @{"Pic 1" link  ExtraContent/Images/HDMI_Splitter.iff/MAIN} which makes it easier 
to switch from AGA to RTG modes though sometimes I still have to go into 
the monitors settings to switch from VGA to DVI modes which only takes a 
few button clicks.

So now that you have your monitor situation installed the first thing we 
need to do is to get a copy  of Picasso96 which can be found on Aminet:

=> (https://aminet.net/package/driver/video/Picasso96) 

or you can purchase the latest updated version which is still being 
developed today at Individual Computers website:

=> (https://icomp.de/)

Second thing is to download the latest VideoCore.card file at the 
Emu68-tools nightly builds website: 

=> (https://github.com/michalsc/Emu68-tools/releases)

With both files downloaded you can install Picasso96 from it's built in 
installer and make sure to click on one of the graphics cards on the first 
install screen (it doesn't matter which one as you'll have to rename it 
later on).

Continue with the installation clicking 'proceed' button at each step until 
completion BUT DO NOT RESTART your Amiga instead copy the VideoCore.card 
file you downloaded in step 2 to LIBS:Picasso96.

Next go to DEVS/MONITORS and you will find the graphics board you already 
chose on the first Picasso96 install screen. You can change the name to 
something else if you wish or keep it as it is as the name of the file 
itself doesn't matter. Next open the 'Information' about the graphics board 
icon and go to 'Tool Types'. Locate the entry "BOARDTYPE" and change it to 
"BOARDTYPE=VIDEOCORE". Now make sure to click save before closing the 
screen!

Now you can safely reboot your Amiga 1200 and go to your Prefs folder on 
your Workbench and open Picasso96Mode. Next create a new setting by dragging 
the "New Setting" icon to the Setting screen area. You can now give this new 
setting a name and attach it to the VideoCore board by clicking on the 
"Attach setting to" pull down screen at the top of the window (it should 
show Board0:VideoCore or whatever name you gave it). At this point you can 
choose and test the built in screen modes shown on the right hand of 
the window by clicking the "Test" button. Once you've tested screen modes 
that work with your setup save changes to Picasso96 and your Amiga 1200 will 
reboot. 

Now you can go back to your ScreenMode Preferences and you should see all 
the new RTG VideoCore screen modes listed which you can select and save the 
setting you wish and enjoy your PiStorm32 with Emu68 and RTG!

After using RTG for over a month now I can truthfully say that it works 
flawlessly with no noticeable lag or screen defects on all the programs I 
normally use. The only downside (which is rather minor) is that the AGA to 
RTG does not switch automatically as noted above.

@endnode

@node eludepistorm "How to run Elude demos on a PiStorm"
@toc guides
=============================================================================
         @{b}How to run Elude demos on a PiStorm@{ub} - by: @{"John Scolieri" link johnscolieri}
=============================================================================

How I got my favourite ELUDE demos working again after installing my 
PiStorm32-lite Amiga 1200 accelerator. 

With my 060  accelerator in my Amiga 1200 (running Amiga OS3.2) I just 
double clicked on the executable file form Workbench and the video started 
up great but this wasn't the case after I installed my PiStorm32 accelerator 
but with the power of IconX and TextEdit (or your favourite Amiga text 
editor) the problem can be solved as follows:

Note: For this example I'm running Elude's Kakao (AGA/RTG) demo released in 
2012 at Revision

 1- Open up your text editor

 2- Type the following line without quotes "eld-kakao -double -rtg" (if using 
    AGA type 'aga' in place of rtg).
   
    Note: eld-kakao is the executable demo file.

 3- Save the text file as "kakao-runme" (or click me 1st etc.) in your kakao 
    demo folder

 4- In Workbench go to your kakao demo folder and right click on the 
    kakao-runme text file created in step 3 and click on the 'Icons' tab at 
    the top of screen and scroll down to 'Information'

 5- Click on the 'Icon 'tab and click the 'default_tool' button and choose 
    "SYS:C/IconX"

 6- Click 'Save'

 7- Now you can go into your kakao demo folder and double click on the 
    "kakao-runme" file and enjoy the demo in all its AGA or RTG glory !

 8- Now you can do the same thing for all your other favourite Elude demos.

I've attached a few screen shots so you don't miss any spaces like the 
first time I tried and wondered why it wasn't starting ;-)

