@endnode

@node lightwave101 "LightWave 101 - Rendering DEMs"
@toc guides
=============================================================================
       @{b}LightWave 101 - Rendering DEMs@{ub} - by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
=============================================================================

If you are familiar with VistaPro then you probably have already heard of
DEMs, for those not initiated by VistaPro let me explain a little about the
DEM format. DEMs are 2D maps used by the U.S. Geographical Survey as a way
to describe terrain shape and elevation. The entire globe has been surveyed
this way including some planets in our solar system. Downloading and 
rendering pre-made DEMs is great but what if you want to create your own
DEM for use in VistaPro or even better in LightWave?

@{b}We meet again old friend ...@{ub}

Creating a DEM file is very easy, however you need to make sure you use the
right software for this. In most cases I work with Brilliance but for some
reason and the author was never able to find out why, ScapeMaker did not
like IFF files made in Brilliance. So you will need to load up good old
DPaint. ScapeMaker can import two sizes (258x258 or 514x514) of IFF files 
for conversion to the DEM format however since we want to save out the
DEM file as a LightWave object we are limited to former size (258x258).

ScapeMaker works by reading the luminance values i.e. dark and light as
elevation data, white being the highest point and black the lowest point.
It also has certain requirements regarding file size and bitplane depth.
24-BIT, IFF64, HAM or anything with more than 6 bitplanes will not be 
accepted. 256 colour or grayscale low-res to high-res however will
be loaded by ScapeMaker.

Armed with this information let's load up our old friend DPaint, remember
to set the image size to 258x258 and a maximum of 256 colours. However in
this case I suggest using 16 as we will be working exclusively in 
greyscale. Once you have DPaint loaded, we will need to create our pallete.

This is accomplised by using the menu, finding the 'Color' item, and 
selecting 'Pallete' and then 'Mixer' from the sub-menu. A new panel will
appear, set the last colour to white and the click on the black colour and
select 'Spread', click on the white colour next and a greyscale spread will
appear in the panel. You can now click 'OK' to go back to the main screen.

Now the fun part starts, remembering that white is the highest elevation
and black is the lowest draw an image, text, or logo. It might help to draw
on paper first what you plan the image to look in 3D to help with applying
the elevation values correctly. Save out the file as an IFF and then be 
ready to move onto the next part.

@{b}ScapeMaker@{ub}

ScapeMaker v4 is the version that supports LightWave obj creation, however
first we need to load the greyscale image we have created in DPaint. Once
you have loaded ScapeMaker you will see two black windows with buttons
above. Make suree 258x258 is selected and then click on 'LoadIFF'. When
you have first loaded the IFF nothing will appear on the screen, you
need to press 'MakeDEM'. A greyscale image of your IFF will appear, if it
is not showing the whole image you can select 'Region', your image will 
appear with a floating window, drag out the window to cover your whole
image and then click the close gadget. Click on 'MakeDEM' again to see
your whole image.

If you save your DEM as it is, it will be only saved as a VistaPro DEM to
save it for LightWave we need to copy some files into RAM before saving
the file. ScapeMaker v4 comes with 5 pre-formatted LightWave objects 
which need to be placed in the RAM disk when saving a DEM for LightWave.
They are a '258x258' sheet divided into 4 quadrants of 130x130 points of
which there are 4 of them as objects. The 5th and final file is a 
pre-formatted LightWave obj 'sheet' that covers the entire '258x258'
object but at half the resolution, which gives you an objct of 17,500
polygons. With these files in the RAM Disk when you save the DEM 
ScapeMaker will look for the files and automatically create a LightWave
object from your greyscale IFF image. From there it is a simple job of
loading the object into LightWave, coloring or texturing it and then
rendering. With this approach you can also import VistaPro DEMs and
convert them to LightWave objects to create spectacular scenes.

I hope you have enjoyed this short guide on ScapeMaker and LightWave
and as we reach our 12th issue after this one it might be time to
say goodbye to the LightWave series of tutorials for a while and 
concentrate on some other 3D software. If you have a particular piece
of 3D software you want to learn more about contact us and let us know.

@endnode

@node samplenoise "How to Reduce Noise in 8 Bit Samples"
@toc guides
============================================================================
 	@{b}How to Reduce Noise in 8 Bit Samples@{ub} - by: @{"Roald Strauss" link roaldstrauss}
============================================================================

DISCLAIMER WARNING: This article is written for the Amiga audiophiles only! 
Anyone reading this article, whom does NOT identify as an Amiga audiophile, 
assumes full responsibility for any mental and/or physical damage it might 
cause them. Neither the author nor WhatIFF? Magazine can be held liable for 
any emotional trauma caused by reading this article. Proceed at own risk!

@{b}The Quest For Less Noise@{ub}

I began my exploration of the Amiga Protracker MOD format way back in the 
early 90s, and have created many MOD files in the 30 years that has passed 
since then. It became a passionate hobby that I've kept exploring till this 
day.

Despite many new modern trackers being available nowadays, I still find the 
4-channel 8-bit MOD format more intriguing. The challenge in the limitations 
are simply more fun than having no limitations at all. So despite actually 
buying one of these newer and much more modern DAWs in recent times, I use 
Milkytracker to create my tracks 99% of the time nowadays.

It's been fun to be able to still discover new things about the MOD format 
even here in recent years. New techniques for making various effects. 
Alternative ways of putting things together. And most recently I began 
experimenting with ways to reduce the noise in the 8-bit samples.

Prior to these experiments I often asked around on various Amiga oriented 
chatrooms about ways to reduce the noise in 8-bit samples, but the only 
feedback I ever got was that it just wasn't possible.

Unfortunately I'm the kind of person who doesn't believe what people say. 
Probably because past experiences have taught me that most people don't 
actually know what they're talking about. The more they sound like they 
know, the less they actually know.

Therefore I often end up going on the quest myself at some point. And that's 
what happened in this case too. I wrote this article afterwards in order to 
share my discoveries with you.

Before getting started, I assume you know about the obvious:
- Make sure the 16-bit sample has a high an amplitude as possible. Even 
  consider using compression in order to boost the overall amplitude
- Likewise, don't fade the amplitude in the sample - use commands for that 
  instead.

Right. Let's get started then. Here's how to minimize the noise in 8-bit 
samples when converting from 16-bit.


The first (wrong) info
======================
If you search for something like "how to remove noise in 8-bit audio", you 
will typically get a lot of results explaining that you need to apply 
"dithering" in order to get rid of something called "quantization noise".

Aha... and what exactly is dithering and quantization noise then?

Well, quantization noise (sometimes also called quantization distortion) 
is the noise that is created when reducing the bitrate from 16-bit (65536 
distinctive sample values) to 8-bit (256 distinctive sample values). One 
technique for converting 16-bit to 8-bit is simply to truncate the 16-bit 
sample, which basically means to just take the 8-bit byte part of the 
16-bit sample. This means that a 16-bit value between 0 and 255 will be 
converted to the 8-bit value of 0. And the 16-bit value between 256 and 
511 will be converted to the 8-bit value of 1, and so forth.

In other words, each 8-bit value will lose precision with up to 255 values 
compared to the 16-bit signal - and that's what's called quantization - 
because every 255 values gets reduced to a single value. And it is this 
lost data that causes the noise. The noise is actually the sound of the 
missing data.

Ok, so what is dithering then, and how is that supposed to solve this? 
Well, dithering is simply the process of "adding random noise" to the 
signal in order to hide or disguise the quantization distortion, and 
give back the audio a more natural sound. It supposedly replaces the 
quantization noise with a "white hissing" noise - which apparently many 
people prefer instead.

And there are many different kinds of dithering. The most common one is 
called Triangular Probability Density Function (TPDF), and you can apply 
such dithering to your sound with the following SoX command:

sox 16bitinput.wav -b 8 8bitoutput.s8 dither -S

Ok then, so far so good. Sounds interesting. But when we search for these 
things online, we tend to forget a simple but important reality: It's not 
1995 anymore, and all of these articles about dithering are written by 
losers who doesn't even know what an Amiga is. They use socalled "modern 
professional" equipment, and often don't even talk about 16-bit to 8-bit, 
but rather 24-bit to 16-bit or even 32-bit to 24-bit. And the samplerates 
they use are usually 96 kHz or more.

Therefore, the dithering techniques they describe does not give the same 
results when targeting 8-bit 16 kHz, like we do on (stock) Amiga. Mainly 
because of the low samplerate we use.

The human ear can hear frequencies between 20 hz and 20 kHz, and is most 
sensitive to frequencies from 2 kHz to 5 kHz. Some people can even hear 
as low as 12 Hz and as high as 28 kHz. (And it is of course typically in 
this group you will find the audiophile people).

When you apply dithering to a 96 kHz signal - i.e. random small values on 
each sample value - it effectively becomes a frequency of its own that 
varies between 24 kHz and 48 kHz - meaning well outside the human hearing 
range. That's why it works. That's how you effectively move the noise away 
from the human hearing range.

Not so on Amiga though, because here we typically use samplerates between 
8 kHz and 27 kHz. If we apply dithering to a 16 kHz sample, we're 
effectively adding a noise frequency that varies between 4 kHz and 8 kHz - 
which is no where near outside the human hearing range. It actually happens 
to be in the frequency range we are most sensitive to. In other words: 
It's the exact opposite result of what we're looking for. We're not getting 
rid of the quantization noise, but rather just adding an extra layer of 
"white hissing" noise on top of the quantization noise. So now we have 
noise with extra noise, which is easy to hear on the TPDF dithered sound 
given by the SoX command above. Useless.

But wait. There is also something called "noise-shaped dithering". Let's 
take a look at that then.

Noise-shaped dithering to the rescue?
=====================================
Basically, noise-shaped dithering is where you try to shape the dither, so 
that it becomes not so random anymore, again with the purpose of moving the 
noise to a different frequency. A simple noise-shape dithering technique is 
done by subtracting each sample value (of the applied noise) with the 
previous sample value. Because this will give a bigger chance of a higher 
frequency. So for a 44100 Hz signal, instead of the noise ranging between 
11050 Hz and 22050 Hz, it will now be closer to 22050 Hz - which helps, 
because that's outside most people's hearing range. But for a 16 kHz sample 
on Amiga, it's still not a whole lot helpful. It'll merely bring the noise 
frequency closer to 8 kHz, which is still very audible to all of us.

For this reason, most of these noise-shaping dithering methods won't even 
let you process files with such low samplerates that we use on Amiga. The 
only one that will is called Shibata. And the SoX command looks like this:

sox 16bitinput.wav -b 8 8bitoutput.s8 dither -s -f shibata

It will be less noisy than the TPDF dithered output, but compared to the 
original truncated 8-bit version, it will sadly not reduce the noise at all.

At the low samplerates we use on Amiga, we don't have the option of moving 
the noise to a higher frequency outside the human hearing range. Our only 
option is to move it to a lower frequency. And SoX doesn't seem to do that.

Noise-shaping without dithering to the rescue then?
===================================================
There is another tool out there called "Shibatch Sample Rate Converter". 
Like most of the SoX dithering methods, SSRC also refuse to work with lower 
samplerates. Lucky for us though, I'm a super hacker, so I took a look at 
the source code, and did some messy hacking experiments with the options. 
(Basically I just changed a couple of numbers so that the tool wouldn't 
dismiss my attempt using a lower samplerate than those supported, but if 
anyone asks, I was a super elite WhiteHat haX0r Uber geek who changed the 
world for the better - or better yet: Say that it can't be done any better! 
That way, we know someone will invest loads of time and effort to prove us 
wrong and provide an even better method in the near future).

I simply changed one of the profiles to "54264 Hz -> 27132 Hz". So that I 
have to feed it a 16-bit 54264 Hz file, to get an 8-bit 27132 Hz file back. 
To do this I obviously have to convert my 44100 Hz file to 54264 Hz first:

sox my16bit44100hz.wav -D -r 54264 my16bit54264hz.wav

And then I run my SSRC command:

ssrc_hp --twopass --bits 8 --dither 0 --pdf 1 0.1 --rate 27132 my16bit54264hz.wav my8bit27132hz.wav

Notice I apply "--dither 0" which means I'm not actually doing any dithering 
anymore. This is all "just" noise-shaping. And that's probably the key.

I have no clue about inner workings of SSRC, but I can clearly hear a 
difference between this SSRC result and the previous SoX results - also 
when using 27132 Hz for the SoX command too. SSRC gives a much better 
result with far less audible noise.

The problem with these techniques though - both noise-shaping and dithering, 
is that it never actually removes the noise. It merely moves it to a 
different spectrum in the audio. And because it varies which frequencies 
different people hears best, there will always be some people who hear 
*more* noise in the samples where *you* hear the *least* amount of noise. 

So what do we do?

Well, the only thing we can do really, is to consider the majority and/or 
trust our own hearing as musicians and pick whatever method *we* find the 
least noisy. Googling around seems to indicate that most people are very 
happy with the results that SSRC produce. And I definitely agree, despite 
my messy "hack" to allow 27132 Hz output.

So SSRC is definitely on the list of useful methods to reduce noise in our 
MODs. But the downside is that it forces us to use a samplerate of 
27132 Hz... And that's another thing to keep in mind when using the SSRC 
method: As soon as you play the sample at other samplerates, the 
noise-reduction effect may disappear. It may even result in more noise than 
the truncated sample will give.

Manual noise-shaping
====================
Ok, so dithering is off the table. Dithering is no friend of Amiga. We do 
not like dithering. Noise-shaping seems to be the way forward though. So 
let's experiment some more with that.

SSRC is definitely on the list of useful methods, but surely we must be 
able to find more useful techniques? Preferably some that doesn't require 
us to use - and stick to - a samplerate of 27132 Hz. It would be nice with 
a method that can be used with lower samplerates, and which allows us to 
actually play the sample at different samplerates without losing the 
noise-reduction effect.

Let's take a look at manual noise-shaping on one of the most noisy samples 
in 8-bit: The sine bass.

I've created a few tools of my own that I use for this. First I use a 
little command-line tool to create a 16-bit C-1 sine tone in 16726 Hz. I 
then load this file with another small tool I made, which gives me a 
little simple graphical display of the 8-bit conversion along with the 
quantization noise that's created from the conversion (amplified to better 
see it).

Looks like this: @{"Image 1" link  ExtraContent/Images/image1.iff/MAIN}

I can then manually adjust each sample value in order to shape the 
quantization noise into something a bit more smooth or soft.

Looks like this: @{"Image 2" link  ExtraContent/Images/image2.iff/MAIN}

The result of this process is that the white hissing noise gets replaced 
with a harmonic distortion. The hissing noise is gone, and instead I have 
a socalled overtone mixed with my sine - which I very much prefer instead 
of the noise.

So to me, this is also a good solution for getting rid of the noise, and 
rather effective in the case of a sine sample. But it's not that easy to 
apply to all kinds of samples. The more complex the sound, the more 
difficult it is to find "pretty" shapes for the quantization noise.

The least amount of quantization
================================
For the next experiment, we will pick the sample values that results in the 
least amount of quantization. If for example we start at a 16-bit value of 
10, and the next sample value is 240. Then the least amount of quantization 
for the 8-bit samples would be 0 and 1, instead of 0 and 0 which will 
normally be the case for a truncated 8-bit sound. That way the quantization 
will be 10 and 15 instead of 10 and 240, which will logically reduce the 
noise a bit - move it to a lower frequency - but it will also change the 
actual sound. It will kind of constantly move the DC offset, and can 
therefore easily result in the sound moving outside the available amplitude.
Comparing a normal sound with the sound produced by this method, we can see 
how the sound wanders off and leaves the window.

Normal Sample:
@{"Normal Image" link  ExtraContent/Images/image3.iff/MAIN}

Sample with least amount of quantization per sample:
@{"Least Amount of Quantization Image" link  ExtraContent/Images/image4.iff/MAIN}

While it's clear for me to hear that the noise has indeed been moved to a 
lower frequency, it's also clear to see that this approach will only work 
for short sounds.

14-bit remains the ultimate solution
====================================
The final method on the list is the 14-bit trick, in which you need two 
channels and two samples. One 8-bit sample played at full volume + one 6-bit 
sample played at volume 1. This will give you a 14-bit'ish quality output, 
which gives the absolute best result of all the options - despite using 
lower samplerates.

So which method is the best?
============================
Well, the best method is the one that works best for the specific case. Most 
of the time, the best result is produced by using a mix of different 
methods. Because each method has advantages and disadvantages.

Method        | Advantage             | Disadvantage
--------------+-----------------------+-----------------------------
Dithering     | No advantages at all! | More noise
--------------+-----------------------+-----------------------------
SSRC          | Moves noise down      | Must be 27132 Hz
--------------+-----------------------+-----------------------------
Manual shape  | Noiseless!            | Harmonic distortion
--------------+-----------------------+-----------------------------
Least amount  | Moves noise down      | Wanders off
--------------+-----------------------+-----------------------------
14-bit trick  | Best result!          | Requires 2 channels & sounds
--------------+-----------------------+-----------------------------

The SSRC method is useful when needing to play snippets of recordings, e.g. 
when you have downmixed many channels into a single sound.

If you can't accept needing to use a samplerate of 27132 Hz for this - and 
if your sound is a short one - you can opt for the least amount of 
quantization method.

The manual noise shaping works best for short chip sounds.

The 14-bit trick has the disadvantage of needing 2 channels and 2 
instruments, but it doesn't necessarily require more bytes than the SSRC 
method. I've found this method to be rather good for creating basslines 
with far less noise than plain 8-bit bass sounds has.

And that concludes my noise-reduction experiments. I hope some of you found 
it useful. :-)
  
@endnode  

@node brilliance101 "Brilliance 101 - Exploring the Dither Tool"
@toc guides
============================================================================
 	          @{b}Brilliance 101 Part 10@{ub} - by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
============================================================================

Hello and welcome back to the 10th part of the Brilliance 101 series, this
time round we are going to look at a very simple but effective tool if you
have only a limited palette available. Often you will see dithering used in
games on the Amiga and also on the Megadrive and SNES, it was a standard
tool/effect to be used before we have thousands of colours available in
game.

To get access to the dither settings you will need to find the 'Draw Mode'
button on the right side of the panel. A right mouse click will bring up
the panel. We will be working with the buttons 'Dither 1' and 'Dither 2'
and using the sider at the bottom. But first a quick explanation of the
differences between 'Dither 1' and 'Dither 2'. When you select 'Dither 1'
with the dithered pattern being the current selected colour and the areas
with no paint being always black. You can change the intensity of the 
dither by using the slider at the bottom on the panel. If you want a uniform 
dither then sticking to the values of 10 is a good idea, i.e. 10%, 20%, 30%
and so on.

With 'Dither 2' paint is applied to the image in a dithered pattern using 
the currently selected colour and the background colour. Like 'Dither 1' the
intensity of the dither is controlled by the slider. Of the two I find
'Dither 2' to the most useful since I can change the space colour between
the pixels to another colour. Please remember that if you are painting with
a background colour no dither pattern will appear as the dithered colours
will both be the same. 

You can use 'Dither 1' and 'Dither 2' with any of the paint modes, even 
with text, which can prove to be quite useful. Free hand painting with the
dither tool can give you some neat effects and it pays to play around with
it.

That is it for this issue, a rather short tutorial, however next issue we
will delve more into the 'Draw Mode' options and see what other tricks are
possible from there.
                                             
@endnode           		   

@node imagefx101 "ImageFX 4.5 101 - Basics Part 1"
@toc guides
============================================================================
 	          @{b}ImageFX 101 - Basics Part 1@{ub} - by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
============================================================================

ImageFX is probably the best image processor there is for the Amiga, 
however with this power comes complexity and it can be a bit tricky figuring
out how to do things beyong scaling or adding simple filters. In this guide
we will look at creating a digital summer holiday postcard. While this guide
was done with ImageFX 4.5, most of what is done can be done in ImageFX 2.

If you anything like me then you probably have drawer full of photos from
your holidays. Being it 2023 they are most probably digital photos and
making our task much easier than 28 years ago. To begin with find a photo
that you want to be your main image, for my example I chose a shot of a
beach from Amami island. The photo is quite large, over 4,000 x 4,000 
pixels. Now while this is fine for modern day systems the old 2MB of chip
ram in your Amiga can barely hold an image that size, so either resize it
on your Mac/PC or do it the correct way, resize it in ImageFX. This is 
easily accomplished by loading the .jpg file, this will probably take a
while so go grab a cold drink and some snacks while you wait. Once the
image has been loaded all you need to do is click on 'Size' and set the
height and width. For our postcard lets use a high res but friendly 
1024 px by 768 px, once it has finished scaling save the file as an IFF.

Now we have to choose our other images that we will paste into the main
image. The same process as above should be followed but to help save
Chipram reduce the size of the images to 500 px by 500 px.

In my example I found a photo of the lovely breafast that we had eaten
at the hotel. What I want to do with the photo is shrink and create a
pespective effect. This can be accomplished with the 'Transform' button.
A window/panel will pop up with several types of transformations, select
'Perspective 3D Rotate'. A grid will appear over the image buffer, by
clicking and holding the left mouse button you can rotate the image. I
wanted to create an angled image, my settings were:

	Rotate X = 35
	Rotate Y = -34
	Scale X = -25
	Scale Y = -25
	AntiAlias = On
	Locked Ratio = On

Take note of Scale X and Y, this is very important as if you leave them
as is your image will be cut off at the edges. Using the slider you can
shrink the image so the edges will not be lost. Once you have your settings
as you like them, click on 'Preview' to see if anything needs to be 
changed.
	
Now we will need to cut out the modified image, I have tried in the past to
find an easier way using mattes but without a manual I had to try it another
way. If someone knows of another way to do this please contact me at the
magazine so I can update this tutorial accordingly.

So on to cutting the image, you will need to click on the 'Full' button and
select 'Poly', then draw an outline around the perspective altered image.
We need to cut out the image next and this is done by clicking on the 
'Brush' button, a selector will pop up and you will need to choose 
'Pick Up Region'. Next go back to your main image and you will see the cut
image has replaced the mouse cursor, find a spot that you like and press 
the left mouse button to paste it down.

To recap what we have done so far is to bring in our main image, the post
card background if you will, reduced it to a more manageable size. Then
brought in another image, reduced it, transformed it using the Perspective
3D Rotate, cut it out and pasted it on the main image. What we need to do
next is bring in some more pictures and do the same but changing this time
the Perspective 3D Rotate settings, experiment and use the preview as much
as you can to save time.

Once you have set your images its time to give the main image a bit more
pizzaz! Find the 'Effects' button and choose 'Lens Flare', if you left click
on the top preview image you can position the flare where ever you want, to 
increase the size of the flare left click, hold and drag the mouse sideways
to change the size. Use the Preview box at the bottom to see if you are
happy with the results and then click on 'Okay'. Finally to give our post
card a more postcard'ish look, find the 'Arexx' button, when you click on
it a requestor will pop up, choose 'Border.ifx', you can leave the border
width to 10 or more. This will put a nice white border around the card
making it ready to be sent to all your other Amiga buddies or uploaded to
Aminet. Here is an @{"example" link  ExtraContent/Images/TestImageFX.iff/MAIN} of the results you should expect.

That ends our first ImageFX guide, I hope you found it useful. Right I am
going to go and grab a cold drink before I melt before my Amiga in this
summer heat. Until next time, Amiga Forever!

@endnode         


@node moderneffects "How To Create Modern Effects In Oldskool Trackers"
@toc guides
============================================================================
   @{b}How To Create Modern Effects In Oldskool Trackers @{ub} - by: @{"Roald Strauss" link roaldstrauss}
============================================================================

Many of the modern DAWs available nowadays comes with a lot of built-in 
effects, we can use: Echo, reverb, phaser, lowpass filter, highpass filter 
etc. All with "automatisation" options too, which allows you to change the 
levels of the effect dynamically. Fancy stuff!

But for some of us, the oldskool way of tracking just remains the most 
appealing and intriguing option. Producing oldskool formats like MOD, XM, 
S3M and IT that can be used on older classic platforms, instead of creating 
the bigger sized streamed formats that can only be used on the more modern 
platforms.

But these old formats generally doesn't offer such fancy effects options, 
so what do we do there? Simple: You simulate the effects.

In this article I will describe how you can achieve the following cool 
effects in these old formats - even in the 8-bit 4-channel MOD format:
@{i}
- Echo
- Reverb
- Phaser
- Surround sound
- Lowpass filter
- Highpass filter
- Bitcrunch
- 14-bit quality in an 8-bit MOD
@{ui}
There are of course many other kinds of effects you can create with the old 
formats, such as Timestretch (using 9xx). But this article is not about the 
available built-in effects-commands. This article is about how to achieve 
other effects that isn't officially supported by the format(s) with effect-
commands, but rather effects you can achieve mostly by playing two samples 
at the same time.

Now, obviously you can always achieve most of these effects simply by 
merging the effect into the sample itself: Load the sample into Audacity 
and apply the effect. Then replace the boring-effectless-sample with this 
new sample-with-awesome-effect in your track.

And I'm not saying that's a wrong way to do it in some cases. I use this 
approach myself sometimes, depending on the effect and the track. But 
merging the effect(s) into the sample will give a rather static result - 
always the same amount of the effect. And that's not an optimal solution 
in my humble opinion.

In this little guide, we'll focus is on how to achieve a more flexible 
version of these effects, where you can adjust the levels dynamically in 
your track, thus ending up with much more variation of the effect.

@{b}1. Echo@{ub}

The most simple of them all. All tracker musicians (should) already know 
about this one. It is no doubt the most used effect in the list, and no 
one would ever think about merging this effect into the sample. I'm just 
including it here to make it a complete list.

To add an echo to a channel, simply copy the channel of the pattern to 
another channel - insert a few empty rows at the top for the delay, and 
reduce the volume of all notes. That's all there is too it. And you can 
do this multiple times, thus using multiple channels to produce a bigger 
echo effect.

You can also add some panning on the echo-channel(s) (if supported by the 
format), to enhance the echo-effect further.

The dynamics of this effect can thus be controlled with the volume and 
panning of the echo channels, and of course how many channels you want to 
use.

You can hear an example of such an echo effect in my track:

	Happy_Sunrise_HQ_8bit.mod 
	=> https://www.indiegamemusic.com/5098

@{b}2. Reverb@{ub}

To create a dynamic reverb, we first need to produce a sample of a reverb.

Load your sample into Audacity, and apply some heavy reverb effect. If the 
effect is strong enough, the actual instrument will be almost gone, and 
only reverb will be left - which is what we're going for here.

Normalise and apply Compressor a few times to boost the reverb. Then create
or find some good loop points, so the reverb continues forever.

This way you'll have a reverb sample to go with your actual instrument. 
We're not merging the reverb effect with the sample in this approach. We're 
merely producing a separate reverb sample to use. One that is really loud, 
and thus needs to be played in a different channel at a low volume.

What's the difference in the actual result, you ask? Well there are two 
advantages with this approach: First, you can now adjust the level of 
reverb you want, in the actual track using volume commands, rather than in 
the sample. This can thus be dynamic through-out the whole track.
Second, because the reverb sample is normalised and compressed, and thus 
played at a very low volume, it'll practically be noiseless in an 8-bit MOD. 
Had we instead merged a low reverb effect into the sample, it would have 
been rather noisy in an 8-bit MOD, due to the mix of low amplitude and 
quantization noise.

The dynamics of this effect is thus controlled by the volume of the reverb 
sample, and how many channels you use. An instrument that only uses 1 
channel, could easily use 3 additional channels for the reverb sample.

But we only have 4 channels available in Protracker of course. So in an 
alternative approach that only use a single channel, we can merge the two 
samples together: Merge the instrument sample with the compressed and 
normalized reverb sample. This approach is mostly useful for short 
instruments though, and the idea is that you fade the volume of the sample 
to reduce reverb. The more reverb you want, the less you fade the sample.
The advantage with this approach is that you only have to use a single 
channel. You can hear an example of such a dynamic reverb effect in my 
track: 

	Connections-MOD
	=> https://www.indiegamemusic.com/5430

@{b}3. Phaser@{ub}

A phaser effect is achieved by playing the same sound in 2 channels 
slightly out of phase.

In case of a looped synth/chip sample, a phaser effect can be achieved by 
copying the instrument to another instrument, and adding a finetune on one 
of them. Playing both samples at the same time will then create a looping 
phaser effect. And because we used finetuning on the instrument, we have 
the effect column completely free for other effects.

Alternatively, you can use the same sample in both channels, using 
finetuning effect command on one of them. For a MOD you can use commands 
E1x and E2x. For an XM there's Xxy available for even finer tuning. You can 
also get some funky effects with 4xy. Any command that controls vibrato and 
portamento makes the dynamics of this effect.

@{b}4. Surround Sound@{ub}

You can turn the phaser effect into a surround sound'ish effect simply by 
panning each channel to each speaker.

@{b}5. Lowpass Filter@{ub}

Low- and highpass filters are essentially the removal of high or low 
frequencies. To create a dynamic lowpass filter on a certain sample, first 
load the sample in Audacity and apply a highpass filter. (Yes, you read 
that right - apply the opposite filter of what you want in your track).

Then invert the sample (also known as boosting the volume minus 100%).

Now load this highpassed inverted version of your sample into your tracker, 
and play it with the original sample at the same time. Make sure they're 
both panned the same.

You will now only hear the low frequencies of the sound, because you're 
playing the inverted high frequencies of the same sound at the same time 
with the same panning, effectively removing the high frequencies, thus 
resulting in a lowpass filter. Setting volume on the inverted high 
frequency sample will determine how much of the high frequencies to filter 
away. Full volume = All high frequencies removed. Low volume = Very little 
high frequencies removed.

Creating a lowpass filter this way will give you

- One normal sample
- One highpassed sample
- Dynamic lowpass result

You can hear an example of such a low pass filter done this way in my 
track: 

	Unshackled.xm
	=> https://www.indiegamemusic.com/4797

That's 64 levels of lowpass + 1 level of highpass.

This approach requires 100% precise timing of the player though. 
(Read more about that later). For an alternative way of achieving a 
simulated lowpass filter, you can simply create the lowpass sample in 
Audacity, and play that together with the normal sample, slowly decreasing 
volume of one while increasing volume of the other. That approach won't 
require precise timing, but you'll miss the highpassed sample as the other 
approach will give you.

@{b}6. Highpass Filter@{ub}

To create a highpass filter is done the exact same way as the lowpass 
filter, except of course you select the lowpass filter in Audacity instead 
of the highpass filter.

Any equaliser effect you want to dynamically filter out can be achieved 
this way.

You can hear an example of a high pass filter done this way in my 
track: 

	Back_to_Basics.xm
	=> https://www.indiegamemusic.com/3352

@{b}7. Bitcrunch@{ub}

A bitcrunch effect can be achieved much the same way as the low- and 
highpass filters are done. Simply run your sample through a filter that 
cuts off the upper or lower bits, depending on what effect you want. Then 
invert the sample, and play both at the same time. Again you have the 
dynamics available by adjusting volume of the effect-sample.

For example, you could split an 8-bit sample into two 4-bit samples, 
producing a rather rough noisy sound, that you can slowly fade away and 
back using the volume.

outbytelow = (inbyte & 0x0f);
outbytehigh = (inbyte >> 4);

@{b}8. 14-bit quality in an 8-bit MOD@{ub}

The same way you can play two 4-bit samples in an 8-bit environment to 
produce 8-bit sound with the bitcrunch effect, you can also play two 8-bit 
samples in a 16-bit environment to produce 16-bit sound. This may not sound 
a whole lot interesting at first. Why split up a 16-bit sound into two 
8-bit samples like that? Because: This technique also works on certain 
older platforms, such as the Amiga, where you officially only have 8 bits 
available, but technically the Paula soundchip is capable of more: It can 
achieve 14-bit'ish quality. I will skip the technical explanation, and just 
say that you can - by splitting a 16-bit sample into an 8-bit part and a 
6-bit part - actually get 14-bit'ish quality on Amiga. (The "ish" part 
means "Definitely much better than 8-bit, but probably not quite true 
14-bit"). And who wouldn't love that bass to be less noisy?

A 16-bit sample consists of sets of 2 bytes. Shift the first byte of each 
set 2 bits to the right, and save all these bytes as "6bit.raw". Save the 
other byte as "8bit.raw".

Play the 8-bit sample at full volume, and the 6-bit sample at volume 1.

outbyte6bit = (inbyte1 >> 2)
outbyte8bit = inbyte2

You can hear an example of and 8-bit MOD with 14-bit quality in my track:

	Happy_Sunrise_HQ_14bit.mod 
	=> https://www.indiegamemusic.com/5098
and also in: 

	Sneaky_Chick_14bit.mod
        => https://www.indiegamemusic.com/5052

(Try turning on/off channel 3 in Sneaky Chick to the difference.) 

A note about low/highpass filter, bitcrunch and 14-bit

Low- and highpass filters, as well as bitcrunch and the 14-bit trick all 
require precise timing in order to work, because the two samples has to 
play 100% synchronised.

This is not a problem for the XM, S3M and IT format, since all trackers 
and playerlibs for those formats has such a precise timing.

But trackers and playerlibs for MOD files sadly aren't consistent when it 
comes to precise timing. In other words, these tricks won't work with all 
trackers and playerlibs for the MOD format. So if you insist that your MODs 
must play correctly everywhere, you should avoid using these tricks.

But if you only need your MODs to play correctly in the productions where 
they're actually used, go ahead and use these tricks all you want. Just make 
sure the playerlib thati s used, handles the MOD(s) correctly. This can be 
done simply by listening to the track(s) when played in the game.

I've had game-developers help me test playback of MODs using these tricks 
on various platforms, and so far it seems that the only platform that has 
issues is the Amiga, and only with Protracker 3.x
 
Protracker 2.3d handles them fine. Same with Hippoplayer and Delitracker. 
EaglePlayer only handles the tricks for the right speaker though. The built
-in playerlib in AMOS also supports them fine, tested on A500 and A1200.

So I'm seeing a lot more players that support these tricks, than players 
that don't.

Now go have fun playing with these effect-simulations. :-)

@endnode
       		   
