@node customvsstock "Custom Music vs Stock Music"
@toc articles
============================================================================
         @{b}Custom Music vs Stock Music@{ub} - by: @{"Roald Strauss" link roaldstrauss}
============================================================================

There comes a time in any ongoing game development project, where the game
-developer has to make up his mind about whether he wants to find a 
musician to do custom music for his game, or if he can settle for the stock 
music alternative; finding existing ready-to-use tracks in the style and 
mood that matches the game.

Meanwhile, all the world's musicians have the exact same choice to make: 
They must also decide whether they prefer to do project work or stock music.
The target platform doesn't matter. Whether it's a homebrew game for a 
classic platform like the Amiga, or a commercial game for a modern platform, 
it's still the same decision both parties has to make.

From the game-developer's perspective, having custom music tailored to the 
game obviously sounds tremendously appealing. "What could possibly fit my 
game more than music that has been specifically written for it?"

But it's not always the holy grail the majority seems to think: The 
musician doesn't always live up to the vision and expectations of the game
-developer, and sometimes it sadly doesn't take more than that for the whole 
project to slowly crumble and collapse. In the case of a commercial project, 
custom music is usually also much more expensive than the stock music 
alternative.

From the musician's perspective, project work typically pays a lot more than 
stock music does. But it also requires much more time and effort to create - 
and being instructed on how to do the music can often kill the passion, 
which can easily affect the quality of the end result.

These pitfalls doesn't automatically render project work useless of course. 
There are lots of game-developers and musicians who manage to avoid these 
problems, and have a thriving teamwork for many years. I'm merely saying it 
shouldn't be considered a bullet proof golden path to succes.

For me personally, as a much bigger artist than businessman, I basically 
want an approach that lets me stay passionate about my music - which means 
I absolutely have to have the freedom to create exactly the style and mood 
I feel like, when and how I feel like it, in my own pace, for whatever 
platform(s) I feel like, in whatever filetype(s) I find interesting at the 
time, and without having a stressing deadline to worry about. It's all 
about artistic freedom for me: I just want to make the music that I want to 
make, when I want to make it. And then game-developers can take it or leave 
it. It would of course be nice to be able to earn a little pocket money on 
my music, but all the other factors weigh a *lot* more. I am *much* more of 
an artist than a businessman.

While wanting all of those things for myself, I of course also realise that 
the game-developer has a similar list of things *he* wants: Be able to 
acquire high quality music that fits his game perfectly, with a matching 
genre and mood, in the filetype that his platform and development 
environment requires, that has a certain max filesize, max channel use to 
leave room for sfx, all at a low cost - and of course delivered before the 
deadline.

So the question is: Does such a model even exist? A single recipe that 
delivers all the wishes from both parties at the same time, despite having 
such opposite interest?

In my experience: *Yes!* That is *exactly* what stock music can do for both 
parties.

I've been composing music for over 30 years now, and have been offering my 
tracks to game-developers via IndieGameMusic.com for half of that time.

Here's what I've learned during those 15 years.

In reply to the most frequent statement I keep hearing in the "custom music 
vs stock music" debate: "Stock music will never fit the game as well as 
custom tailored music".

Well, apart from the already mentioned pitfalls with that approach, I've 
simply lost count on how many times I've put a stock track of mine online 
at IndieGameMusic.com thinking "This doesn't sound like game music at all. 
No one will ever request this track", only to be contacted 6-12 months 
later by a game-developer with the words: "Wow! This track is literally 
*perfect* for my game!"

The first couple of times I experienced this, I was rather surprised, 
because I hadn't expected anyone to find that track usable at all - and 
definitely not decidedly "perfect". But over time it made more and more 
sense to me. Of *course* that track is perfect for his game. It makes all 
the sense in the world. The keyword being "world" here.

*Any* track anyone makes will of course be perfect for *some* game out 
there in the big world. It's merely a matter of how long it takes for that 
particular game-developer to decide to create this game of his, and 
subsequently how long it takes for him to find the track online. And 
IndieGameMusic.com has a ton of search options to help the game-developers, 
so that part shouldn't take long.

And that's it really. That's the short and simple explanation of how stock 
music becomes an equally good option as custom music, for both the game-
developers and musicians.

"But what if the game-developer wants exclusive music then", I hear someone 
yell out in the back. "Yeah! And how can the musician even earn a decent 
penny with this approach?", someone else joins in.

The answer to both of those questions is: "Licenses".
Just because we're talking stock music doesn't mean the game-developer 
can't get exclusive tracks. IndieGameMusic.com gives both parties plenty of 
options here:

If money is of no object to the game-developer, and if he insists on being 
the only one in the world using the track(s) for his game, then he can 
search for tracks available with an Exclusive Resale license. Tracks that 
hasn't been used for anything yet can be offered exclusively, and they will 
usually still only cost about half the fee that the equivalent custom music 
would cost.

Should the game-developer wish to pay even less, he can go for a mix of a 
Non-exclusive Resale license + a Platform Exclusive license for the 
specific target platform of his game. Buying the Platform Exclusive license 
prevents other game-developers from using the same track on the same platform.
For newer platforms, this will typically cost the game-developer about 25% 
of the fee he would have payed for the custom music equivalent. And for the 
older classic platforms, such as the Amiga, it's typically less than 10% of 
the price for custom music.

Going even cheaper than that, the game-developer can also choose to settle 
for a Non-exclusive Resale license (without a Platform Exclusive license). 
Tracks sold with this license can be sold many times to many different game-
developers on many different platforms, which is why the price is typically 
only between 5 EUR and 20 EUR per track. And that's why this license is the 
most attractive one for both parties. Many sales for the musician, and very 
inexpensive for the individual game-developer. But obviously not a solution 
for those game-developers who want the music to be solely associated with 
their game.

Finally, there are also quite a lot of musicians who offers their tracks 
with a Freeware license. This means game-developers may request to use the 
track free of charge *if* their game is also free of charge. Notice that 
this license requires that the game-developer doesn't make money on the 
game in any way.

So as you can see, there's a *lot* of flexibility with usage and prices.

"Ok ok, but how does the musician earn a decent penny on this then?"

Simple: By offering a Non-exclusive Resale license + several Platform 
Exclusive licenses for his tracks. That way, the musician only needs to 
sell this combination of licenses 3-4 times in order to have earned the 
same he would have made on doing the same track as a custom one.
Or alternatively, sell the Non-exclusive Resale license alone 10-20 
times.

To increase the chances of selling a track multiple times, it's a good 
idea for the musician to make the track available in a filetype that can 
actually be used on multiple platforms - and/or make it available in 
multiple different filetype formats - and/or make it available in multiple 
different qualities and filesizes. In other words: The musician must engage 
himself in the impossible mission of "pleasing everyone". Did you make a 
4-channel 8-bit Protracker MOD below 80 kb? Then you can convert it with 
SNESMOD to a format compatible with the Super Nintendo. You can also use 
Timidity to convert to MIDI, or use 2MIDI from Un4Seen to convert to a 
MIDI+SF2 soundfont.

Offering the track in many different filetype versions logically increases 
chances of selling the track multiple times to different game-developers on 
different platforms. But it also increases chances of selling the track 
exclusively - to game-developers who is targeting multiple platforms with 
their game-project, and thus needs the same track(s) to be compatible with 
many different audio systems. Additionally, some game-developers who are 
targeting a classic platform, such as the Amiga, sometimes has to settle 
for a lower quality version of the music in the game itself, because of 
memory / channel / bitrate / samplerate limitations, and therefore 
sometimes want to include a CD with the soundtrack in a better quality with 
the physical release.

So to summarise: I recommend that the musician tries to offer his tracks in 
both WAV, MP3, OGG, XM, MOD and more if possible - all in multiple 
different bitrates and samplerates and qualities.

"Fine, but how often does the musician sell 3-4 Platform Exclusive licenses 
then? Or 10-20 Non-exlusive Resale licenses?", the sceptic continues.

I admit, this is something that requires a lot of waiting. But it does also 
depend on the track of course - and luck. I've sometimes sold a license 
just a few days after putting the track online, but at other times it took 
2 years before I sold one.

This time span between sales is the only "cost" of choosing to do stock 
music instead of project work. But then again, I don't see how that differs 
a whole lot from the time the musician would sit around waiting to get 
hired for project work.

Of course, the target platform(s) matter too. As a musician, I'm obviously 
not expecting to get rich of making MOD files for Amiga games. I create 
those filetypes purely out of the nostalgic passion for my childhood 
computer, and also because I want to support game-developers on the classic 
platforms in general.

But it's not completely impossible to earn some pocket money on the old 
formats either. I'm actually seeing quite a lot of interest in the MOD 
format. Admittedly not so much from Amiga game-developers though. My 
biggest MOD customers are actually Atari Jaguar developers. Gotta love 
that MOD can be used on so many platforms. But I hope to hear from more 
Amiga game-developers in the future. ;-)

Here at the end, I would like to encourage all Amiga composers out there 
to put your MODs on display at IndieGameMusic.com. Help out the game-
developers on the Amiga (and other classic platforms) find music for their 
future projects, by building a nice stock music library with the filetypes 
they need. Thank you.
  
@endnode

@node amigamagazines
@toc articles
============================================================================
    	@{b}Amiga Magazines - Yesterday Today@{ub} - by: @{"Ivan Sorensen" link ivansorensen}
============================================================================

Greetings Checkmarks. Today I am going to talk about Amiga magazines and 
specifically as an Amiga fan in 2023.

Growing up in Denmark, we did have a couple of computer magazines with an 
interest in the Amiga, the most notable being the magazine known as Det Nye 
COMputer (among a few name changes) before the castle walls finally fell 
and it transitioned to being a PC-only magazine.

This was a decent magazine with the usual mixture of productivity articles, 
game reviews, hardware reviews, industry interviews and so forth. Not a bad 
magazine at all really, though the level of professionalism certainly 
varied over the lifespan. The letters page was often quite lively with the 
Amiga vs PC debates of the day.

However, I did not have a chance to look at the UK and US Amiga 
publications until many years later when I was able to find scanned archives 
of them online (many are available on archive.org these days). I have come 
to quite appreciate these magazines and so I wanted to talk about what they 
can offer you, from the perspective of someone living in 2023 and reading 
many of them for the first time.

Of course, the most immediate use is nostalgia: Reading about various 
pieces of kit that were being released, marvelling at the prices of a 
20-megabyte hard drive and revelling in the excitement of the Amiga 3000 
announcement. Nostalgia often gets a bad reputation in retro computer 
circles, but I think we are all prone to indulging in it at times, 
especially for something that was often a formative experience in our 
relationship with technology. And I suspect you are mentally better off 
spending an hour reading about Kickstart 1.3 than spending an hour 
scrolling on Facebook.

For those trying to understand the history of home computing, magazines are 
also an important view into what the general outlook was at the time. Amiga 
fans are quite prone to pet peeves (Piracy killed the Amiga! Doom killed 
the Amiga! Ranger! ST ports!) And it can be quite helpful to get an insight 
into what the actual thoughts were at the time. With online access being 
far more limited, magazines often acted as the common social ground for 
users and are often the best way to gauge what reactions were to a 
particular product or development.

Many of the bigger magazines were aimed at a more professional audience 
(Amiga World) or a general user audience (Amiga Format, CU Amiga) and would 
include tutorials and guides on topics from computer graphics to 
programming to using specific applications. These tutorials remain as 
valuable as ever for people looking to use their Amiga in the present day. 
In many cases, tutorials on specific topics can actually be difficult to 
find online and video formats suffer from being slow and inefficient 
compared to a concise written guide.

Game players of course benefit greatly from magazines. Game reviews could 
occasionally baffle and frustrate, but it can be valuable to see what the 
reaction to a game was before the internet forums settled on the one true 
answer. You may be surprised to see that many games considered mediocre 
today were rated quite well, while some fan favourites had frosty 
receptions. Perhaps a useful reminder that when it comes to whether a game 
is fun to actually play, it matters less if it has 4 levels of parallax or 
3.

Gaming-oriented magazines often featured walkthroughs, cheat codes and 
hints as one of their main draws. These can be a lot of fun to try out on 
their own (some have errors or only worked on specific versions of the 
games, and others were straight-up hoaxes) but they are also often not 
documented well online. Sometimes the only answer to solving a particularly 
devious puzzle may lie in an old copy of Amiga Format!
 
A final word of course needs to be said about cover disks. These were disks 
with demos, artwork and sometimes full games or programs that came with the 
magazine. Later they would be replaced with CD options in some cases. Cover 
disks seem to have been more of a feature in the UK magazines and some 
users were able to satisfy all their productivity needs with cover disk 
programs.

Many of these have also been archived online and from a historical 
perspective, it can be a lot of fun to check out a cover disk after reading 
through that particular issue of the magazine. The concrete value is perhaps 
a bit lower these days, as the full version of a particular game is 
generally only a download away.

Of course, you could run an experiment where you rely entirely on cover 
disk games and programs for your Amiga entertainment and productivity needs. 

Hmm, Ill be right back, downloading some cover disks.

@endnode

@node tokyoretro
@toc articles
============================================================================
    	@{b}Tokyo Retro Computer Users - One Year Later@{ub} - by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
============================================================================

Living in Japan is an amazing experience, and over the 17 years that I have
been here, it has grown to become my home. While there are many great things
about Japan, being an Amiga user is a bit more tricky. The Amiga was a 
presence here and there is hardware available and thanks to the Internet it
is very easy to order all sorts of hardware delivered to Japan. However one
aspect that I miss are the Amiga meetups and shows, in Europe and the States
the Amiga is well catered to. But in Japan not so much, so when the
opportunity presents itself to meet other Amiga users I generally jump at
the chance. One year ago I wrote about my experience at the Tokyo Retro
Computer Users meet up, there I met three other Amiga users and got down
to some serious Amiga discussions. I had always wanted to go back but due
to work or other commitments it was always difficult to make it. But 
finally my schedule lined up with a meet date.

On the 26th of August I woke up to another blistering hot day, my A1200
was packed up in a gym bag ready to travel with me. I took the train
from Inagekaigan station on the Keiyo line to Hatchobori station and
proceeded to the exit on the map I had printed out from Google Maps.
Confident this time that I would not get lost I exited the station and
strolled in the scorching sunshine with my A1200 slung over my back.

After about 20 minutes of walking I was quite lost, not having a smartphone
meant I had to rely on my other GPS. So a quick call to the wife and she
got quickly onto Google Maps finding my position from the surrounding 
buildings and guided me back to the station and then onwards to my
destination. I must say thank you to her for putting up my with Amiga
obsession and lack of direction.

Arriving about one hour late I got the building and quickly changed into a 
clean shirt, paid my entry fee on the 5th floor and then took the lift
down to the 4th floor to meet the rest of the gang. When I entered the
refreshingly cool room there was a small group of people already there
working on their computers. Edoardo came over quickly to say hi and he
also had my A600 board that he had repaired, upon taking removing the
IDE cable four pins came off with it. He had kindly offered to replace the 
IDE connector. Shortly after that I met Sven who recently bought an A1200
and has been slowly building it up. This time he came with his Z80 mini
computer that has evolved from a small motherboard into a fully encased
mini computer with SD card slot and all the necessary IO ports.

This time around I also brought my A1200 in it's translucent case and
new keycaps, I had wanted to see if someone could help me with an issue
with the A314.device driver guruing on me when I did a cold boot. Sven was
able to figure out a solution for this and I am testing the solution at
this moment, if it continues to work I will publish the it in the next 
issue.

Soon other regulars arrived, Michelle brought a very small portable TV and
was working on how to fix an issue of wavy lines appearing on the screen.
Eventually it was traced down to a dodgy power supply, it seems this quite
often the case with older hardware. She also brought along a stack of SNES
games and hearing the sounds from Zelda brought memories rushing back of
my youth. Another memeber Tom had brought an MSX to play games on and had
a remake of Adventure from the Atari 2600.

It was at the point I remembered that I had installed some new games on my
A1200 for *ahem* review purposes and decided it would be nice to get some
game time in, so I managed to rope in Sven and Edoardo for some gaming on
CyberPunks 2 and our exclusive last issue Hamulet. The latter caused the 
most interest when I explained how the game was using HAM mode.

It was a quiet group this time around and while no other Amiga hardware
was on display there was a new person I met who lives only 2 stops away and 
is a big Amiga fan. It was a pleasure meeting you Greg!

The rest of the was spent working on Michelle's SNES, Greg was having some
troubleshooting done on his halfway built IMSAI replica.  Saburo was back
doing an RGB upgrade on his Intellivision replacing the RF out signal. It
was amazing to see him work on such delicate and small board using his
smartphone to figure out what needed to be done.

However all too soon the time came for everyone to pack up, Greg kindly 
offered to drive me back since he is so close to my area. It was fun ride
back packed full of Amiga talk. The next event is slated for the end of 
September and I hope that I can make it. If you wish to join or just find
out more then please visit the meet's website:

www.monochromeeffect.org

PS: You can find me there in the red shirt!
 
@endnode

