@node rno "RNO Developer Interview"
@toc talkingamiga
============================================================================
	          @{b}Interview - RNO Developer@{ub}
============================================================================

@{b}1. Thank you for taking part in this interview, you are the author of 
the RNO series of software, can you explain a bit about why you started the 
RNO series of programs?@{ub}

Hi, and thank you for showing interest in my creations :)

I've always been a passionate music consumer, and for the last couple of 
decades I've mainly listened to music on my MorphOS machines when at home. 
I have created many support scripts for audio players with ARexx and with 
Lua too, that's after Lua was integrated as a modern ARexx replacement for 
MorphOS. As a side note, the Lua implementation in MorphOS supports 
existing ARexx ports, etc., which is very useful.

One thing I was missing when listening to music when I was not sat in front 
of my computer, was to have some kind of a front-end screen with larger 
text, so that I could see which song was playing even when I was at the 
other side of a room. I got some inspiration from the music player for the 
PS3 console, and started to wonder if could I produce a similar solution 
with cover image support, etc.. It would also be nice if it would work with 
multiple audio players.

Plain scripting languages weren't quite enough for the plan, or would have 
become too hacky with external requirements, and with C it would have taken 
way too long for me to produce a reliably working program with the features 
I wanted. I started to look at other alternatives and the Hollywood 
programming language seemed to be a promising option for this kind of 
"multimedia" oriented program. It had functions to show images in layers 
with effects, networking support, ARexx support, and so on. It was also 
based on Lua, which I had already learned, so I decided to give it a try.

Hollywood's documentation is incredibly good and it has an active support 
forum, so I got into it quickly. After a while RNOInfoScreen, the first 
application in the "RNO series", was born. Programming with Hollywood was 
really fun and time efficient, so I was able to be productive with it and 
started to fulfill other ideas I had.

@{b}2. What does RNO stand for?@{ub}

RNO is a demogroup that I've been involved with since the late 90s. The 
name comes from 'Rave Network Overscan' originally, but we just use the 
abbreviation nowadays.

It's difficult to come up with program names that wouldn't have been used 
by other programs, and that's why I started adding RNO in front of my 
application names. I guess it's some kind of branding now, but it was just 
for the easi(lazi)ness at first :)

3. The programs are available across a variety of Amiga platforms 
(Classic, MorphOS, OS4.1) what programming language do you use for 
developing the software?

I've been using Hollywood for all my recent multiplatform applications. 
It's a cross-platform multimedia-oriented programming language, that 
originates from the Amiga, and has some Amiga specific features too. It's 
based on the popular Lua scripting language, even though it's pretty much 
hidden within Hollywood's own functions.

You might ask why Hollywood? Well, I'll try to keep it short. Even though I 
know C to some degree, and have even created some Amiga demoscene 
productions with it over the years, I don't feel comfortable enough to make 
well behaved/stable utility programs with it for our platforms. C is a 
low-level language where a single mistake can lead to catastrophes on Amiga 
related platforms where we don't have proper memory protection for legacy 
reasons. You would also need to learn low-level operating system specific 
coding, and generally spend too much time preparing all manner of things 
before getting into actual content production. That said, I still squeezed 
out an RNOInfoScreen screensaver for MorphOS in C, with an embedded LZMA 
packed Hollywood executable in it.

Hollywood, on the other hand, is a high-level language where you can just 
concentrate on producing the actual features for programs and forget the OS 
initialising stuff, etc.. It also doesn't mess or crash the underlying 
operating system or other programs if you create bugs in your code, so it's 
also safer for users in that regard. Finally, as a bonus, a program made in 
Hollywood can work on a dozen of other platforms, that's without any 
adjustments in the code.

The downside of using Hollywood is that it's a bit resource hungry for less 
expanded classic Amigas, but it's really great for Next Generation Amiga 
compatibles and faster classic solutions, or if you want to release any 
programs on mainstream or mobile platforms.

@{b}4. What hurdles have you encountered developing the software?@{ub}

I have written all my recent applications under MorphOS, and development 
itself has been quite painless generally. I've found some Hollywood bugs 
and made some feature requests, but nothing that would have stopped me 
completing the programs before getting fixes or features in Hollywood 
itself. Hollywood's author is very active at fixing bugs and you can be 
sure they're fixed in the next version - if you just report them!

The biggest hurdles I've encountered are with external dependencies on 
other platforms. In theory Hollywood programs should work equally well on 
all platforms if there are enough resources, but in practise that is only 
the case when you're using Hollywood's core functions with its own windows. 
RNOInfoScreen and RNOPDF are good examples of programs that just work on 
every platform without issues, because they're built around Hollywood's 
internal features.

If you use external GUI toolkits (like MUI with a separate plugin for 
Hollywood) or other external programs, there are differences and 
difficulties between platforms. For example, there's 'classic' MUI v3.8, 
but then there are also newer MUI branches, and a clone (Zune) with 
incomplete compatiblity. I've also used external Shell commands from my 
programs, but even some core Shell features differ (like output- 
redirections) and LhA ports are from entirely different branches on some 
platforms, etc.. All this takes time and effort to test and solve, and in a 
worst case scenario you don't find a solution at all, but I'll say more on 
that topic in the next question.

@{b}5. Which platform has been the most difficult, and easiest, to develop 
for?@{ub}

MorphOS has been the easiest to develop for, as it has the latest official 
MUI, based on the work by the original author, and the OS is also very 
compatible with Commodore's AmigaOS. Pretty much everything I've tried to 
do has worked on it virtually straight away, with only a few issues.

There have been some issues with the unofficial MUI branch on OS4, but the 
issues I've faced have now been fixed. OS4 itself dropped some legacy 
support at one point, which was a problem until a work-around was developed 
in Hollywood. Also, a long-standing very annoying crash issue was finally 
traced back to OS4's codesets.library, and now there's a fixed version 
available.

So, in the current situation I can say that both MorphOS and OS4 are the 
easiest and most trouble-free platforms to develop for, from my point of 
view, with the tools I use. Both operating systems also have the required 
libraries built-in, which is way easier than hunting down all those 
dependencies - as on OS3.

So, then as to the harder platforms to develop for ... 68k as a platform is 
so diverse nowadays that it becomes difficult to develop and maintain 
programs on it.

As there are new AmigaOS versions that aren't fully compatible with the 
original OS. For example, the newer versions from Hyperion have created 
several incompatibilities and fundamental changes to Commodore's original 
AmigaOS versions, which has given me some grey hair. At one point I just 
had to make separate executables of my programs to pre- and post AmigaOS 
v3.1.4, prior to me finding work-arounds or otherwise getting fixed.

On the hardware side there are these quasi-software based solutions around 
FPGAs and SBCs, etc., and it seems that their internal software development 
lags behind in most cases, which can be seen as compatiblity issues. For 
example, I've been banging my head against a wall with the unpredictable 
behaviour of FPU versions of my software with Vampire setups. We've been 
tracking it back, all the way, to the C compiler used by Hollywood and 
finally to the FPU implementation in Vampires. At the moment I should just 
say, please don't use the FPU versions of my programs on Vampires - until 
their emulation gets better!

Finally, most 'real' "Classic" Amiga setups have the "legacy" MUI v3.8 
installed, but many emulation setups are using later "Next Generation" MUI 
implementations. If I use newer MUI features in my programs, I have to 
implement checks as to which MUI version is discovered and then have 
specific code with disabled features for older MUI versions.

All in all, it's impossible for me to test my programs on all "68k" 
varieties out there, and I just can't guarantee quality, and user 
experience, with my 68k compiled programs in every situation, which 
annoys me a bit.

AROS (x86) is a whole different beast, and the most difficult to develop 
for from my point of view. None of my programs have worked straight away 
under it, and I always have to make some modifications and work-arounds 
to get them to work as intended, or at least in an acceptable way.

Zune (MUI clone on AROS) doesn't support newer MUI features and even 
legacy MUI v3.8 compatibility isn't complete. I've come across tens of 
features that don't work, or work with glitches, or just crash. I've had to 
change my design, drop some features when running on AROS, just accept some 
glitches, or even forget an AROS version entirely due to Zune.

Certain Hollywood plugins aren't available for AROS, making it impossible 
to complete some of my programs. HTTPS support (internal or external) has 
been non-existent until more recent efforts, but it's still very buggy - 
too much for my uses. Some basic OS features don't work as they exist in 
other Amiga compatibles, for instance, I couldn't find a way to redirect 
'stderr' in Shell. I also had to write a custom solution to run ARexx 
scripts, and so on! You never know what will crop up when trying to run a 
new program under AROS for the first time. All these surprises make AROS 
development more laborious than others.

On top of that, AROS is available in many different varieties. First of all 
I tried to test my programs under Linux hosted versions but they were 
really crashy. Apparently native versions should be more stable, and my 
current setups under VMware feel better. It's still hard to tell if an 
issue is due to AROS itself or the platform/distribution you're running it 
on.

As a final note, I've also released some WarpOS programs, but I have no 
access to 'real' hardware. All I can do is to test them under MorphOS, 
which runs WarpOS binaries, but there seems to be some nuances between the 
real hardware CSPPC and BPPC. So, it's kind of difficult to develop 
"blindly" for WarpOS, but I still think that classic PPC users will 
appreciate that a program can run on a PPC rather than on a 68k. :)

@{b}6. You have created a large variety of software, which one are you most 
proud of?@{ub}

It's difficult to choose, because I'm pretty proud of them all. I'm proud 
of the philosophy behind my programs, which is to make them simple looking 
and simple to use, but still have powerful modern features 'under the hood' 
that you haven't seen with other programs. To concentrate on what you 
really want to achieve with a program and find a fresh approach to its 
implementation. Sometimes people are too stuck with 'traditional' thinking 
and don't see all the coolness in my programs. :D

If I'd have to mention some programs anyway, I'm pretty proud how modular, 
and "effective", RNOEffects is for an image processing program. Each effect 
is in its own include file, and it's just a matter of removing or adding 
only one line in the main source code to enable or disable an effect. When 
enabled, the effect will be listed in a pull-down menu and is available for 
batch conversion, image combining, ARexx controlling, icon exporting, and 
so on. Every effect can be used in all those features, so it's nice that 
you can use all effects in a freely selectable order within it, for 
example, a batch conversion process. Most other programs just offer a 
limited custom selection of processing effects for these special features. 
RNOEffects also offers some nice tricks for alpha transparent graphics, 
which are harder to do on more traditional image processing programs.

RNOWidgets just looks so cool and uses 3D hardware accelerated layers on 
MorphOS and OS4, which is a true Next Generation feature to get realtime 
alpha transparent window backgrounds to make irregular shaped windows, etc..
Widgets are highly configurable in their appearance and you can use semi-
transparent foreground images to create, for example, glossy effects over 
actual widgets, which offers a modern touch with them.

Finally, I can't forget a glowing mention for RNOTags, which is an ultimate 
solution for ID3 tag editing. It can load just about any possible variation 
of tag and it's quite a sophisticated program in its own right, but more 
about that shortly.

@{b}7. Which RNO program was the most difficult to create and why?@{ub}

Even though it's taken time to develop some other programs too, the most 
difficult was, and still is ... RNOTags.

I was longing for a good ID3 tag editor to edit metadata on MP3 files, 
first on the Amiga and then on MorphOS, but years passed and I still wasn't 
pleased with anything I found. Programs either supported ID3v1 tags only or 
had only limited support for ID3v2 frames. They also didn't support 
embedded images, actually broke tags, or were just prone to crashing. I run 
MorphOS with its internal memory tracker enabled, as it's a good way to 
catch buggy programs, and it revealed that the 68k program I used most was 
behaving badly. After finding that I didn't dare to use it often, as it was 
usually: "write a tag with my fingers crossed, and reboot as soon as 
possible if it broke something". How carelessly I had used such programs in 
the old days, and it's no wonder my OS3 setup didn't stay stable for that 
many days without rebooting and the filesystem blew up occasionally. :)

When I had made RNOInfoScreen, which supports loading of embedded cover 
images from MP3 files, I really wanted an editor that could insert a cover 
image into MP3 files that they were missing from. So, I started to take a 
closer look if I could make a better program myself.

OK, what's an ID3 tag then? There are old ID3v1 tags, that are placed at 
the end of a file and have static fields for information, which sounds 
easy. Then there are newer ID3v2 tags, that are at the start of a file and 
are quite ambitiously designed. There's just so much content in the 
specifications, that programmers are likely to take shortcuts without full 
support. Then there are several different revisions of both main versions, 
which aren't even backwards compatible always or have some obscure 
definitions that nobody has ever used. What should I support in my program? 

Well, everything of course!

ID3v2 specifications define over a hundred different kind of "frames", where 
each frame contains a certain piece of information about an audio file. Also 
there can be unofficial frames 'in the wild' to add to that amount, and some 
frames can be used several times in a tag. Many ID3 tag editors support only 
a narrow selection of frames, and then just ditch unsupported frames in the 
worst case. It's not OK to delete a bunch of frames when just editing, for 
example, a song title ... as even the internal tag editing options in 
Windows 10 did this when I last tried, sigh.

I wanted to make sure that all possible frames get preserved, even if my 
program wouldn't know what to do with them, but I also wanted users to be 
able to re-arrange or remove them if desired. It meant I'll have to use a 
dynamic list for frames rather than a fixed set of fields like most other 
programs do. I also wanted to allow users to add and edit any possible text 
based frames, and also some binary frames like attached pictures. It should 
also be possible to convert data between tag versions so that users could 
convert ancient tags to more commonly used ones.

OK, now I know what I want, but is there anything to help me in this 
process? Libraries/plugins I could use? No. Example source codes? Well, one 
for reading specific tag versions, but it seemed to have bugs like 
miscalculating tag sizes, and it doesn't help with writing at all, but it 
gave me some inspiration in how to get started. I decided to write 
everything from scratch myself, and handle files byte-by-byte and tags 
bit-by-bit.

I spent several months reading through and then interpreting the 
specifications over and over again, implementing reading and writing of 
tags, and trying to fill gaps on the information. If googling didn't help, 
then I just scanned through a massive collection of MP3 files to find a 
common pattern to make my own conclusion. For example, there is 
contradicting information if text strings should be null terminated or not 
in v2 tags, so I made an educated guess based on scanning of close to 
thirty thousand files from the 90s to current day, but I still left it user 
selectable in case someone else thought otherwise and wasn't happy with my 
default settings. There have also been other programs that create some 
non-standard mess with tags, or didn't overwrite a previous tag, but added 
new ones - resulting in multiple tags on a file, and all that kind of 
unexpected trash within files that my program would be able to handle and 
ideally be able to dispose of somehow. Even though I don't agree with 
everything in it, this old rant may give you an impression about the 
situation when you want ID3 tag support: 

=> https://blog.codinghorror.com/a-spec-tacular-failure/

After all that ground-work, it was time to write the visible part of the 
program, and that became quite complex too. The GUI is very flexible and 
powerful with all frame adding and arranging options, sniffing 
corresponding frames from filenames, caching, copying, and conversion of 
contents, online help for everything, etc.. With all of this taken into 
account, this has been the *most demanding* program for me to write so far.

@{b}8. What plans do you have beyond the currently available RNO programs?@{ub}

Updating current programs seems to be an eternal project, and some of the 
programs should be released on more platforms, but that would need more 
testing. For example, RNOTags isn't widely available, as I planned to 
release it on a certain app store to get some compensation for all the 
effort I put into it, but the plan dried up and the program was left in 
limbo. It's only available for MorphOS as donationware now, but I'm going 
to release it for other platforms myself, in due time. It will take some 
time though, as I started to add a FLAC support for it, which is still far 
from being ready.

Though there are always ideas for totally new software, and the AROS camp 
is eager to fulfill some software gaps, so I get many requests and support 
from there (hi Salvatore!). RNOPublisher, RNOArchive, and RNOTunes were 
born in this way, and there's at least one new program I've promised to 
make.

I have some wild ideas for new apps and it would be interesting to try if 
they'd be do-able, but they might be just too ambitious to start with. I'd 
also want to make a couple of games one day, I already have ideas if I'd 
ever have time from application coding. Also, demoscene compos always 
inspire me to do something myself too, but I don't know if that will 
happen. I don't have any roadmaps or exact plans, it just happens if I get 
a do-able idea or some program needs an update quicker than others, but 
generally I have several programs under development simultaneously and 
they finish when they finish.

@{b}9. Thank you for your contributions to the Amiga scene, do you have any 
final words before we finish the interview?@{ub}

Please give feedback to developers, be it on public forums or email, but 
it's always nice to hear if someone has tried or even uses your programs. 
Even a short comment gives developers a good feeling, and if you've ever 
wanted to code yourself, give it a try as you've no excuses! It's still 
fun despite some challenges :)

Also, thank you for all the people who have supported my software 
development! Thanks to Neil Pearson for being a tireless proof-reader for 
my ReadMes, MorphOS Library articles, and now for this interview too.

Finally, please visit https://jpv.amigaaa.com/ to check out the software 
I've talked so much about! :) There you'll find screenshots, YouTube 
videos, and other information there.

@endnode

@node erikhogan "Erik Hogan Interview"
@toc talkingamiga
============================================================================
	       @{b}Interview - Erik Hogan (Scorpion)@{ub} by @{"Rob O'Malley" link robomalley}
============================================================================

@{i}Scorpion Engine is a game development system for the Amiga and Mega 
Drive Genesis conceived of and developed by Erik Hogan. It is designed to 
be easy to use and flexible, while still providing the performance and 
features needed to create high-quality games. Scorpion Engine is free to 
use, and it is supported by a growing community of developers.@{ui}

@{b}1. Can you share your history with Amiga computers and Megadrive 
consoles? How old were you when you first encountered them, and what are 
some standout memories or experiences you had with these platforms? How did 
your usage of Amiga computers and Megadrive consoles contribute to your 
passion for game development and coding?@{ub}

The Amiga was something I never had as a kid - I grew up on the C64 and it 
seemed like the Amiga was the obvious eventual upgrade path. To that end I 
collected issues of Amiga Power, hoping to have a substantial coverdisk 
games library by the time I finally got my hands on one.

The Amiga upgrade never came - Doom was on the horizon and the general 
consensus at the time was that PC was taking over the computer market. But 
I never forgot how badly I wanted one, and around a decade ago I got my 
CD32. The desire to do something creative with it led me into the homebrew 
projects that eventually became Scorpion Engine.

I don't have that many memories of the Mega Drive specifically, nearly 
everyone I knew was a Master System owner. But there was one standout - I 
remember seeing a demo of Road Avenger in an electronics store, and I was 
blown away by the gorgeous anime visuals (in spite of the lack of gameplay). 
That experience inspired me to do an unofficial Amiga port decades later.

@{b}2. Can you elaborate on the key features and functionalities of your 
game development system that differentiate it from other existing solutions 
for the Amiga and Megadrive and how do you envision your game development 
system addressing the needs and challenges specific to these retro 
platforms?@{ub}

There are three key pillars for Scorpion Engine:

  1. Performance - Scorpion is aimed at making highly performant games on 
     unexpanded Amigas and Mega Drives. While this is a tricky challenge 
     for a generic engine running on vintage hardware, every update brings 
     improved speed through gradual conversion of the underlying codebase 
     to optimised ASM.

  2. Flexibility - Scorpion is designed to be flexible enough to tackle a 
     wide variety of genres. There are projects in Scorpion that represent 
     the platformer, shooter, action-rpg and beat-em-up genres.

  3. Simplicity - Scorpion is meant to be usable for anyone who wants to 
     use it. It uses modern file formats like PNG for graphics and Tiled 
     for map editing, and the codeblocks scripting system is designed to be 
     easy to use without needing to learn programming.

With these three key pillars, it very much is intended to be a 68K 
counterpart to engines like Unity, Unreal, GameMaker and Construct.

There are other game creation engines for Amiga such as Backbone and 
Redpill, both of which are viable options for making a quality Amiga game. 
And there are also game creation engines for other platforms such as 
GBStudio and NesMaker. But for the Mega Drive, the only alternatives to 
Scorpion that I'm aware of require the learning of programming languages.

@{b}3. What advice would you give to someone who is interested in using 
Scorpion Engine to create their own games? What are the best resources for 
learning how to use Scorpion Engine?@{ub}

Unfortunately there's not a lot in the way of good documentation or "from 
scratch" tutorials out there for Scorpion. There's so much to be done on 
the engine and so little time that I have to prioritise rapid progress over 
everything else.

For new users, I'd always recommend just downloading it and tinkering with 
the large number of demos that are included.

There's also a long running thread at EAB that is a common place to ask for 
advice at: 

=> https://eab.abime.net/showthread.php?t=97450 

as well as a growing Discord community on the PixelGlass server at: 

=> https://discord.gg/VpWBCd8TGg. 

The Scorpion community is always friendly and happy to help out newcomers.

@{b}4. What are the plans for future development of Scorpion Engine?@{ub}

The future plan is to continue growing in terms of features, performance 
and platform support. The Amiga will continue to receive specific features 
just for that platform as well as general features that improve all 
platforms. Porting code from Blitz to pure 68k asm to improve speed and 
reduce the size of the engine is an ongoing process.

I've also recently been dwelling on writing a Rust runtime to allow 
Scorpion games to be ported to Windows, Mac, Linux, Web, Android and iOS. 
In addition, support for Neo Geo is tentatively planned in 2024, and Jaguar 
in 2025.

@{b}5. What are some notable projects that have been developed using 
Scorpion Engine, and which projects do you believe best showcase the 
features of the engine? Additionally, what projects would you like to see 
developed using Scorpion Engine in the future?@{ub}

There's so many out there, I feel like I'm going to miss out on some really 
important ones! I do need to apologise for major projects I haven't listed 
below.

I think Mixel's "Creeping Me Out: Hex Night" is by far the largest and most 
ambitious Scorpion project that's ever worked on, there's so much depth and 
variety in it that it's an excellent showcase for what can be done with the 
engine.

Wonderboy by AcidBottle and Green Beret by Dante Mendes also show that the 
engine is capable of handling full length arcade ports. Also, Dante's 
upcoming Castlevania AGA is a good example for how visually stunning Amiga 
games can be.

There's also a handful of games like Boxx 4 (Lemming880) Duckstroma 
(UltraNarwhal) where they're very conscientious about performance, those 
games are excellent examples that show that the engine can run well on 
stock hardware when designed specifically for it.

Aeon's Legend (formerly known as 'Scorpion Boy') is a game that I've helped 
BitBeamCannon on that aims to be the best of both worlds, combining world 
class visuals with decent performance on stock hardware.

So far as games I want to see developed in the future, the number #1 is 
definitely AlarCity - my own, well overdue, running-and-gunning action RPG. 
Finding the time to work on it alongside all other Scorpion projects and the 
engine itself is a challenge, but it's always in the back of my mind and 
every now and again I dust it off and do a little more on it.

Finally, I've always craved a Shantae game or port in Scorpion Engine - if 
Wayforward ever offered me chance to work on a Shantae project, I'd say 
yes in a heartbeat.

@{i}Thanks Erik for taking the time to answer these questions, the engine 
itself is open source and found on GitHub:@{ui} 

=> https://github.com/earok/scorpion-editor-experimental

@endnode

@node gunnar "Gunnar von Boehn Interview"
@toc talkingamiga
============================================================================
	  @{b}Interview - Gunnar von Boehn (Apollo Team)@{ub}
============================================================================
@{b}1. Hello, can you introduce yourself and explain how you came to Amiga and 
   what you do in the Apollo team?@{ub}

My name is Gunnar von Boehn aka 'BigGun'. I was born in 1972 in Braunschweig
Germany. Maybe the city name sounds familiar to you, as Commodore had its 
big European factory in my home city Braunschweig. So, it's no wonder that 
I had C-64 computer myself at a young age. I was lucky that my best friend's 
older brother was very active in the C64-unprotection crew "LCS", which gave 
me plenty of games and my friend and me also learned a bit of coding.

Inspired by the great C64 games we also tried to code games. With my very 
limited skills at that time, I spend a lot time working on a small C64 Indi 
vertical shooter game of a flying dragon named "King of the Air".

Commodore released the Amiga 1000 in 1986 in Germany. The Amiga was totally 
innovative. It was showcased in several local computer stores. The powers of 
Amiga were absolutely impressive. Games like Defender of the Crown blew me 
away. The combination of graphical and musical powers clearly showed how 
advanced the Amiga is. As I did not have the money to buy an A1000 right 
away - I spent most days after school in the computer store trying to get 
my hands on it to play with one of the showcases A1000. Staying each day in 
the computer store I met one day a guy from a very early Amiga cracker group 
"PowerStation" and we became friends.

With a stroke of luck, my parents won a little sum of money, which they 
invested to buy me an A1000 in 1987. I was totally happy - and immediately 
joined the Amiga cracker team "PowerStation" later "Traxxion" later 
"Sinners". Being in this group gave me access to an unlimited number of 
games but most importantly, it gave me access to all the assembly codes of 
their intros and cracktros. I got some good books. the excellent Amiga 
hardware reference manuals, and a 68K CPU instruction book. From then on, 
I was totally focused on learning how the great machine Amiga works. The 
working example codes of the intros helped me a lot to quickly understand 
both the 68k and the powers of the Amiga chipset.

It was clear to me that the Amiga is an engineering masterpiece.

The 68000 CPU is not only very powerful but also very coder-friendly and 
very nice to code on. The Amiga combines the CPU with the very powerful and 
smart Amiga chipset. The idea behind the chipset to have DMA-based 
independent working helpers Sprites/Copper/Blitter etc is genius. 

Some people say school took a back seat, from then on for me.

I would say I spend a lot of time coding intros, demos, and trainers. While 
technically still at school, I had a part-time job at a local video company 
where I programmed video effects for them on the Amiga in assembly. I had 
at that time still my A1000 and later an A2000 with a 68020 CPU accelerator 
card and hard drive. I started dreaming of making a living as an Amiga game 
developer and started coding some games in assembly. "Ravage" was a typical 
Arcade shooter, "Wega Wars" was a Space Explore/Conquer simulation.

After I finished school, I did my military service and then spent my money 
on getting the brand new Amiga 4000 and coded a lot on it. The last major 
project I did on the A4000 was coding a relational database for the Amiga. 

Then catching me by surprise, Commodore went broke.

This broke my heart. :( My plans on making a living as an Amiga game 
developer were blown away. I knew how advanced the Amiga was and how much 
better its internal design was compared to the PC. So wanted to work with 
computers - it was not so easy for me to have to work with the technically 
inferior and to me "disgusting" PC designs.

I worked for a number of computer industry companies. After showing the 
database that I wrote on Amiga I got a job at MySQL. I also worked at SONY 
and later in hardware development at IBM and much later in CPU development 
at HUAWEI.

All the jobs that I got... I got because of the great amount of programming 
and hardware knowledge I had acquired working with the Amiga. It was at IBM 
where I met many other Amigans. We were at this time working together in 
the "CELL" team (heart of PlayStation 3). "CELL" was a joint development of 
SONY and IBM. We quickly became good friends who shared a love for the 
Amiga and talked a lot at lunchtime about how superior many concepts of 
Amiga were and still are. We assumed how wonderful the Amiga is to learn 
programming and learn how hardware works and how elegant the Amiga design 
is. We quickly agreed it was a shame that Amiga did not continue.

We then formed the idea - that Amiga was so great - that it's worth 
reviving and continuing it. Based on this we started the NatAmi (Native 
Amiga) project and our goal was to revive Amiga again. For the Natami we 
needed a CPU, which of course needed to be a 68K CPU. As only the 68K has 
the coder-friendly features which made Amiga such a great computer. As 
Motorola did not produce any 68K anymore. We decided to make our own much 
more advanced 68K CPU.

Which we named "APOLLO" - so this is where the Apollo Project started.

Today I am the team lead of the Apollo-Team and I am the manufacturer of 
the great V4 cards here in Germany.  I spend my day working on computer 
development, core updates, answering user questions or making great 
Amiga-world-domination plans with our team. I enjoy very much working 
together, with a great team of "crazy" computer nerds, who have the same 
dream of giving the 68K the well-deserved status back, so somehow when 
Commodore went bankrupt my quest to revive the Amiga began :)

@{b}2. Can you tell us what the Amiga means to you?@{ub}

The current Amiga landscape is very diverse. A cursory glance at the Amiga 
computing scene through internet searches will reveal a diverse number of 
solutions that aim to revitalise Amiga-experience. Options range from 
preservation-only based 'replica' printed circuit boards to PC's running 
software to emulate of the Amiga. In addition, there are also a lot of 
people to whom the look, shape or feel of the huge, cream housing with 
the rainbow checkmark, seems to be very important.

For the Apollo Team, and of course, especially for me, it is clear that it 
is about the inner values that make an Amiga an Amiga.

	1. The efficient Amiga chipset
	2. The powerful 68K CPU
	3. The freedom of the Amiga OS

The Amiga combined excellent GFX and audio capabilities, with an OS which 
was swift, logical, understandable, straightforward 'and simple' and most 
importantly it left the programmer's freedom and didn't restrict them. 

Combined with a CPU which was designed to make programming understandable 
and made the 'homemade' software development possible for everyone. And all 
this for an affordable price.

Such beauty isn't typically seen in other places today. You will not find 
it on Linux or Windows machines. Even today's 4 GHz PCs do often not have 
the swiftness, they are hard to understand and are absolutely not 
straightforward, they give the users less freedom, and are bloated and 
inefficient, totally the opposite of the beloved Amiga design. It is clear 
that today's Computers are complex to understand and do not make the best 
out of the performance they could have.

That is why the Apollo Team decided to revive this timeless beauty of the 
Amiga architecture. So, the idea of the Apollo-Team is to combine the 
elegance of the Amiga design with modern possibilities and to develop and 
improve an Amiga, in the spirit of the good old times.
 
The vision of the team is not about the marketing, branding, logos or case 
design and of course, it is not about emulation or other ugly workarounds 
to make machines pretend to be an Amiga. 

The Apollo Team's vision is to keep the fundamental inner values above 
alive and regard these as technical beauty and design marvels, which were 
created by brilliant engineers. Dave Haynie, former chief engineer for 
Commodore, once said "The Apollo Team, CPU and chipset innovations are 
truly in the same innovation spirit of the original Amiga inventors. Making 
the Vampire an Amiga, which the original team would have designed too." 

@{b}3. Can you talk about how the history of the NatAmi project started in 
2002?@{ub}

It was in the year 2002 when a group of IBM developers, comprising Thomas 
Hirsch, Jens Kuenzer, Christoph Hoehne, Peter Kaltstein and myself started 
the 'Native Amiga' or NATAMI project. All these enthusiastic computer 
professionals were working for IBM at Cell-CPU-solutions like for example 
'ROADRUNNER' which was at that time the world's fastest super-computer.

We 'Amigans' found each other very quickly during the coffee breaks. We 
spoke about how much better, more elegant and easier the work at IBM would 
have been with the Amiga and how much easier coding for 68K was than for 
IBM's PowerPC and how regrettable it was that Commodore didn't exist 
anymore. 

In the beginning more for fun, but at some point, with a certain crazy 
seriousness, we raved about how nice it would be to revive the Amiga. At 
one of these conversations, it was Thomas Hirsch who said, that he had 
already started redesigning the Amiga-AGA - Chipset and that it was more 
or less working, 'THAT' was the starting signal to rewrite history.

The goal of the NATAMI Team was to reimplement the Amiga architecture 
according to the original clever Amiga spirit. The team had the problem of 
not having access to chip fabrication to build any Amiga chips. So we used 
a Field Programmable Gate Array (FPGA) technology for building the Chipset. 
FPGAs are 'writeable' chips just like a writeable CD-ROM. And just like a 
writeable CD-ROM, it can be used to put your own music onto it. A designer 
can put inside a writeable FPGA his own logic, thereby creating his own 
chips. Using writeable chips is not a new concept. Commodore did this 
already many times and in many Amigas or cards for Amiga often writeable 
chips were used. The 68040 CPU card of the A4000 for example, has ten 
writeable chips on it.

So the team of Amiga-loving colleagues at IBM decided to revive the Amiga. 
After we recreated the AGA chipset and finished Thomas's work, the next two 
steps needed, were to source many 68060 CPUs from Motorola and to build the 
NATAMI main board.

The goal was to create thousands of boards to help to grow the Amiga user 
base and create again a market for new Amiga development.

The reinvented AGA chipset did impress every Amiga fan seeing it. When Bill 
Buck the CEO of Genesi saw it, he proposed to add this AGA chipset to the 
3rd generation of his Pegasos systems. He wishes to create a compatible 
system that could run real Amiga software directly in hardware. But as it 
turned out, this future Pegasos version never came to fruition, so the deal 
never came about.

The Pegasos Systems used a PowerPC CPU from Motorola chip branch Freescale.

The PowerPC chip was originally invented by IBM. As the NATAMI Team members 
were all working at IBM's PowerPC laboratory they were PowerPC experts and 
were programming PowerPC every day. They knew that this chip did not meet 
the requirements they wanted to revive the Amiga. The PowerPC is a fast CPU 
and it is very strong in floating point performance, but it is not 
programmer-friendly at all. And because, in the opinion of the NATAMI- Team 
the programmer friendliness was one of the main aspects of Amiga, the lack 
of good programmability was the show stopper for using PowerPC chips.

We knew that we needed new 68K CPUs to revive the Amiga. The programmer 
friendliness of the 68K CPU was what made coding for Amiga so great. Also, 
we wanted at least the 68060 CPU. If we want to revive Amiga, it should not 
be slower than the Amiga used to be. But getting thousands of 68060s was an 
impossible problem to solve.

Motorola stopped long ago to produce these chips, and you cannot buy them 
anymore. So, we hoped to convince Motorola to produce them again. Thomas 
and I arranged a meeting with Freescale, who is the chip production part of 
Motorola, in Austin Texas in 2008 using the help of Bill Buck, CEO of 
Genesi. Bill Buck had excellent connections to Motorola and arranged the 
meeting for us. The Freescale guys were very friendly and receptive to the 
NATAMI. At the same time, the Freescale vice president made it crystal 
clear that they could not produce the 68060 anymore. 'Sorry Guys, the tools 
are gone, the plans are gone, even the fab does not exist anymore. This 
means we would need to redevelop the 68060 from scratch - but the original 
team of developers is not with Motorola anymore, many are in retirement 
homes now!', he said.

So it was impossible to restart production with their current budget. But it 
was not about money, "Even if you put a million dollars on the table. There 
is no chance for new 68060 processors" Freescale's vice president told 
Thomas and me. 

Despite this impasse, Freescale offered something else. The Coldfire CPU 
family. The Coldfire was interesting to evaluate because the Coldfire is 
some kind of relative to the 68K CPU. The goal of the Coldfire family was 
to use the same good and very human readable 68K instruction set, but at 
the same time to simplify the CPU by leaving a number of instructions out. 
This made the chip both simpler and cheaper to produce than the 68K.
 
But it would have the disadvantage that the missing instruction would trap 
out and need to be emulated by a software library. This concept was not 
new, the original Motorola 68060 CPU, which was used for the Phase5 
Cyberstorm accelerators, already missed some instructions of the 68K 
family. And the missing instructions needed to be emulated in software. 
Emulating in software is of course much slower than execution in hardware. 
And while software libraries for missing instructions could be used from 
Workbench this was not possible when an Amiga game was directly booted. 
This was part of the reason why some games crashed on 68060. The 
performance hit for the missing instructions on the 68060 was manageable as 
only a few needed to be emulated and the majority was executed in hardware.
For the Coldfire the situation was different as it missed a lot more 
instructions, so it was not clear how useful it could be in an Amiga.
 
Back home I was benchmarking the Coldfire and profiled the Amiga OS to see 
how many instructions of the instructions that the Coldfire lacks were used 
by the Amiga OS. The tests clearly showed, that the Coldfire chip was 
relatively weak in-memory performance and the Amiga OS used far too many 
instructions the Coldfire missed. The combination of poor memory performance 
and slowdown by missing too many instructions would result in Amiga OS and 
old Amiga applications only running slowly on it. So, in the end, it was 
obvious that for the NATAMI project, the Coldfire was not suitable.

The Team had to find another solution to bring NATAMI to life. After the 
first shock, Jens and me brainstormed about developing our very own CPU, 
again with an FPGA. 

If you know that IBM or Intel needs about 500-1000 people working 2 years 
on a chip design, this idea was more than crazy. IBM calculates for this 
high amount of man-working- hours typically a development budget of about 
40 million USD for a new chip design.

@{b}4. What was the main idea behind the Vampire/Firebird/Icedrake Acclerators?@{ub}

Many Amiga owners are faithful to their beloved Amiga and continue to use 
them all the years. We have developed the best 68K CPU of the world! Our 
Apollo 68080 not only continues the excellent programmability of all 68K 
it also adds new features to it and reaches a performance no other 68K was 
able to reach before.

Dave Haynie - former Chief Engineer at Commodore International acknowledged 
this and said on Facebook about the V4 technology: "If Commodore had the 
68080 CPU then, Amiga would have ruled the world." 

We believe that our Amiga fans should be supported to use their Amigas as 
long and as well as possible. Therefore we have created accelerator cards 
for them giving them the best 68K CPU and also allowing them to upgrade 
their Amiga chipset to Super-AGA. 

Our accelerators allow owners of Amiga 500/1000/2000/600 and 1200 to upgrade 
their system to the fastest CPU and to Super-AGA, allowing them to play AGA 
games.

Yes, you can finally play AGA games also on your Amiga 500!

All the Amiga owners can use Truecolor, 3D acceleration and 16bit Audio 
features of the newest and best Amiga chipset.

These accelerators create a basis with the same performance and operties 
as our new Standalone V4 Amiga has. Having the same features makes it easy 
for software programmers to develop new powerful games again, which will 
ensure the survival of the Amiga over time.

@{b}5. Can you provide an overview of the Super AGA chipset?@{ub}

I assume everyone knows the great original three custom chips of the Amiga?

The chief engineers in former times named the important audio chip Paula, 
the graphic chip Denise and the management chip Agnus.. The design of DMA 
channels, the power of audio voices, the possibilities that sprites and 
bitplanes offer, the concept of the Blitter is clever and enable the 
programmer to do very cool stuff. Probably the most important and most 
clever is the Copper that has the power to orchestrate it all. This design 
is clever and very elegant, it's creative, and it's even revolutionary 
today! It's a design for the future.
 
Furthermore, the Amiga chipset is very well explained with good 
documentation, and once you understand how it works you can do amazing 
things with it. In my opinion, the Amiga chipset is an amazing masterpiece 
of its own. Understanding the chipset itself means realising that this is 
the work of geniuses!

The chipset is fully DMA based. This means it can play audio, show GFX, 
show sprites (These are small moving GFX elements) or can copy parts of 
the screen just by using the Blitter, without any demand on the CPU. The 
copper, which is a special unit, does help to coordinate all this. This 
DMA-based concept was well ahead of its time. 

Of course, when the Amiga chipset was developed some compromises had to be 
made to save cost. And the original Amiga chip designers planned to add 
many features in future chipsets. It was planned to add modes with more 
colours. In addition there were plans to add Chunky Modes, these modes 
provide some advantage for certain types of games. It was also planned to 
add support for higher quality audio samples like 16-bit audio, more audio 
channels to make sound richer in games. The Blitter 'A the chip which 
copies a lot of Gfx in games. It operates in the original Amiga on 16bit 
and it was planned to upgrade this to 64bit. There were also plams to 
upgrade the Copper and it even to build 3D acceleration into the Amiga 
chipset.

And SUPER-AGA does all this which was ever planned and dreamed of for the 
Amiga. It adds all the features that the Amiga developer has ever dreamed 
of having.

Super-AGA is the Amiga chipset that Commodore might have built if Amiga 
ruled the world today.

@{b}6. What were some of the key features and specifications of the Super AGA 
chipset that set them apart from the first-generation Amigas?@{ub}

The AGA chipset is a great design. The idea to have DMA channels which do 
all the work and offload the CPU is very smart and opens up great 
opportunities, without needing to waste CPU time. The Amiga chipset 
combines many features which increase the efficiency of the system a lot. 
While the Apollo Team admires this ingenious invention, it has to be 
honestly said that there are also limitations in the good old AGA. For 
example, the concept of the Amiga audio channels was great, but the OCS 
audio channels were limited to a 28 kHz maximum sample rate, which was 
excellent at their time but a little below the CD quality of 44khz today. 
The upgrade from OCS to ECS improved this and increased the supported 
sample rate of 56Khz, exceeding even CD quality. The Amiga had 4 DMA-based 
audio channels. Four-channel allows the creation of excellent Amiga MODULE 
music or excellent sound effects for games, but when you want to have both 
at the same time, 4 channels become a limitation.

Having 8 or 16 HW channels would make coding games with both awesome music 
and perfect sound effects a lot easier.

The original Amiga designers were aware of these limitations, and they 
planned to upgrade the AMIGA chipset with 'AAA' to improve audio by having 
more Amiga DMA audio channels and to improve graphics to 24-bit. So, it was 
planned not to replace but to improve the Amiga chipset. With this 
knowledge, it is clear that a Team with so many clever minds such as the 
Apollo-Team, has completely in the spirit of the developers at that time, 
further developed the AGA chipset. In this sense, the Super AGA chipset is 
the next step of the Amiga design.

